{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-adbc35942ba1e430", "type": "tool_result", "content": "0\tContrasting statistical patterns in melodic and molecular evolution reveal distinctive constraints in a culturally evolving system.\n1\tReport GitHub Issue × Title: Content selection saved.\n2\tDescribe the issue below: Description: Submit without GitHub Submit in GitHub arXiv is now an independent nonprofit!\n3\tLearn more &times; Back to arXiv Why HTML?\n4\tReport Issue Back to Abstract Download PDF Abstract References License: CC BY-SA 4.0 arXiv:2607.12673v1 [q-bio.PE] 14 Jul 2026 Contrasting statistical patterns in melodic and molecular evolution reveal distinctive constraints in a culturally evolving system.\n5\tJohn M.\n6\tMcBride 1,* W.\n7\tTecumseh Fitch 1,† ( 1 Department of Behavioral and Cognitive Biology, University of Vienna, Vienna, Austria * Correspondence: jmmcbride@protonmail.com † Correspondence: tecumseh.fitch@univie.ac.at ) Abstract Evolved sequences can be used to infer the rules of evolution.\n8\tOrally transmitted folk melodies are evolved sequences whose similarity to protein sequences (one-dimensional, drawn from a limited alphabet) invites application of bioinformatics methods to study cultural evolution.\n9\tA major obstacle is that melodies encode rhythm, which breaks some assumptions of standard sequence-alignment algorithms.\n10\tWe develop a rhythm-aware alignment method and apply it to 40 , 000 40,000 Irish dance tune variants, enabling the first large-scale automated melodic alignment.\n11\tFour canonical bioinformatics analyses – mutability, substitution matrices, positional conservation, and covariance – reveal patterns distinct from those of molecular evolution, revealing the forces that shape each domain: biochemical and biophysical constraints for proteins; memory, motor, and social biases for melodies.\n12\tTogether the results show that bioinformatics provides a powerful framework – conceptual as much as algorithmic – for studying cultural evolution.\n13\tAlthough the cultural transmission of music has been discussed for centuries, here we show how to analyze it at large scale.\n14\tKeywords: cultural evolution | melody | bioinformatics | sequence alignment | Irish folk music ntroduction Sequences generated by evolutionary processes are a wellspring of information that can be used to infer the rules by which they evolved.\n15\tExamples from language span the decoding of ancient languages, 1 to the development of modern language models.\n16\t2 Analysis of biological sequences allows us to infer evolutionary histories, 3 ; 4 the rules of protein biophysics and evolution, 5 ; 6 and to predict future evolutionary trends.\n17\t7 ; 8 Melodies are also sequences that have been shaped and selected through cultural evolution, 9 ; 10 ; 11 ; 12 ; 13 and hold untapped potential for understanding the rules and history of musical evolution, and thus perhaps of cultural evolution more generally.\n18\tAlgorithms offer a clear route to knowledge transfer from bioinformatics.\n19\tMelodies can be represented as 1-dimensional pitch sequences, and sequence alignment tools can in principle be used to compare melodies directly.\n20\t14 ; 15 However, there are noteworthy distinctions both in the form and the evolution of melodic and biological sequences.\n21\tLetters in biological sequences always represent the same chemical unit, while for melodies, notes have two effective dimensions – pitch and rhythm.\n22\tWhen notes are subdivided into multiple shorter notes, or fused into longer notes, alignment algorithms treat this as a ‘gap’, or an insertion/deletion (indel), 16 but this is qualitatively different from the insertions and deletions that arise in biological sequences.\n23\tThese distinctions can at best lead to suboptimal performance when using bioinformatics algorithms out-of-the-box, but could easily lead to major systematic errors.\n24\tKnowledge transfer from bioinformatics is not limited to algorithms, but also broader methodological approaches to discovering the statistical regularities in sets of sequences.\n25\tKey analyses such as amino acid mutability, substitution matrices, sequence conservation and covariance, all led to important discoveries and are foundational to modern bioinformatic analysis.\n26\t17 ; 18 ; 19 ; 20 ; 21 For example, sequence covariance – correlations between substitutions at different positions – can inform us about how a protein folds, 22 such that we can now predict structure given sufficient co-evolutionary information.\n27\t23 ; 24 Here, we propose that bioinformatics analyses can be tailored to melodies, as detailed below, to uncover general rules underlying melodic evolution.\n28\tAs a case study in how to adapt bioinformatics methods for melodies we focus on Irish dance tunes.\n29\tWe chose this tradition for three reasons.\n30\tFolk tunes in general have the right evolutionary properties, dance tunes in particular are methodologically tractable, and Irish music is uniquely well-documented.\n31\tWe now elaborate on each of these reasons.\n32\tFirst, folk tunes persist in recognizable forms over long periods, change to produce variants, and are subject to cultural selection.\n33\t25 ; 26 Change comes from transmission by ear, which introduces copying errors through limits on perception and memory.\n34\t27 ; 11 Intentional variation adds further change, as melodic improvisation is a valued skill in Irish folk music.\n35\t28 These forces – copying fidelity, conformity bias from ensemble playing, and novelty bias from individual expression – produce an ecosystem of tunes and variants, analogous to genes and their homologues, which can be grouped into tune families based on shared melodic history.\n36\t29 ; 10 Second, dance tunes are especially tractable for rhythm-aware sequence analysis.\n37\tAs they are designed for dancing, they obey strict metrical and structural constraints: 30 ; 31 parts have fixed lengths, contain no rests, and can therefore be aligned without gaps – sidestepping one of the central difficulties of sequence alignment.\n38\tTunes also conform to specific tonalities, with pitches drawn from sets of seven or fewer pitch classes.\n39\tFigure 1: Pitch-only and rhythm-aware alignments.\n40\t(A) Receiver operating curve (ROC) and area-under-the-curve (AUC) values for classifying tunes into families using pitch sequences.\n41\t(B) Illustration of two problems with aligning melodies without rhythm information.\n42\tWe show excerpts of two melodies from the Bronson dataset, alongside the manually-corrected pitch sequence alignments.\n43\t14 Without knowledge of rhythm, the alignment to the ’EFF’ part of the lower sequence will always be ’E-F’ or ’EF-’, instead of the correct alignment, ’-EF’.\n44\tThe region with ’GGGGG’ matched to ’G-GGG’ is not a unique solution.\n45\tOther top-scoring alignment solutions include ’-GGGG’, ’GG-GG’, ’GGG-G’, ’GGGG-’.\n46\t(C) An example of a jig (6/8 meter).\n47\tThese are the first two parts of the four-part jig, “The Lark in the Morning”.\n48\tRepeat lines are highlighted with red circles.\n49\tAfter expanding repeats there are 32 measures.\n50\t(D) The same jig (C) represented in the format used for alignments.\n51\tTo get this we expand repeats, map the notes onto a grid with a standard grid size (in this case, eighth notes), and separate tunes into parts.\n52\tFinally, Irish dance tunes stand out for the richness and scale of available data.\n53\tMultiple dance forms and tonalities produce structured variation that is both diverse and constrained – an ideal combination for statistical analysis.\n54\tThis tradition is also unusually well-documented online, owing in part to the ABC notation format developed in 1994, 32 which made sharing tune transcriptions easy and led to repositories including (but not limited to) thesession.org, which holds over 50 , 000 50,000 community-contributed tunes.\n55\t33 ; 34 ; 35 ; 36 The total number of tunes and variants available in digital form online exceeds 100 , 000 100,000 , a uniquely large dataset.\n56\tThe concept of tune evolution and tune families has been developed over many years, 9 ; 10 ; 37 ; 38 but empirical research on how melodies evolve remains in its infancy.\n57\t14 ; 15 ; 39 ; 40 ; 41 ; 42 Previous efforts involving manual comparison of similar tunes, 43 ; 26 ; 44 ; 45 are not scalable to large datasets.\n58\tAs for computational approaches, most have been dealing with orthogonal topics such as tune family identification, 46 ; 47 ; 48 ; 49 ; 50 or phylogeny.\n59\t51 ; 52 ; 53 In a seminal contribution, Savage et al.\n60\t14 used sequence analysis tools for similar tune identification.\n61\tThey did attempt using bioinformatics tools to align sequences, but due to poor quality of automated alignments had to manually align their sequences.\n62\tThus they compared only 328 328 pairs of tunes, several orders of magnitude lower than the number in principle permitted for a joint collection numbering 10 , 000 10,000 melodies.\n63\tFurthermore, the melodies were encoded in a reduced format that excluded most rhythmic, and some melodic information.\n64\tThus, compared to what has been discovered in biology or linguistics, existing studies on melody evolution have only scratched the surface of what is possible in theory.\n65\tHere, we first show that bioinformatics algorithms are useful for identifying similar tune variants, but not for aligning them.\n66\tWe develop a novel rhythm-aware alignment method suitable for musical traditions with rigid metrical structure.\n67\tApplying it to 40 , 000 40,000 Irish dance tune variants, we run four canonical bioinformatics analyses (mutability, substitution matrices, positional conservation, and covariance) and show that the resulting statistical signatures highlight clear differences between molecular and melodic sequence evolution.\n68\tWe then use the results to devise hypotheses and analyses designed to uncover the constraints that guide melodic evolutionary paths.\n69\tThe analyses reveal statistical signatures that are categorically different from those of protein evolution.\n70\tIn particular, we find that pitch mutability tracks tonal hierarchy, reflecting memory and perceptual constraints on transmission; substitution rates mirror the melodic interval distribution, reflecting motor constraints on melodic motion; positional conservation correlates with metrical hierarchy, and covariance reveals conserved repetition structure.\n71\tThe last two findings are consistent with the long-standing hypothesis that a stable “melodic skeleton” encodes tune identity 30 , and we outline experimental predictions that would test it.\n72\tesults Is pitch sufficient to identify similar melodies?\n73\tDo pitch sequences, without any rhythm or note durations, contain sufficient information for identifying similar melodies?\n74\tIf you attend an Irish traditional music session you can see participants, if they do not know the tune that is being played, using an app – TunePal, 54 or FolkFriend 55 – to query the tune.\n75\tThese apps work well, but their algorithms use both pitch and rhythm.\n76\t56 Whether pitch alone is sufficient has been sporadically investigated with no clear consensus.\n77\tOne study found moderate success on 6 , 000 6,000 Dutch songs, 46 while others used small sample sizes 48 ; 49 or non-standard evaluation metrics.\n78\t14 ; 57 We tested this using the standard algorithm MMseqs2 58 on two large datasets (TheSession, Meertens), amounting to billions of tune comparisons.\n79\tThe algorithm first eliminates pairs that are unlikely to match, then computes percent identity ( PID ) scores – a measure of sequence similarity – for the remainder using local alignment.\n80\tThe overall true positive rates – including pairs eliminated at the pre-filtering stage – were 0.71 (TheSession) and 0.42 (Meertens).\n81\tThus pitch alignment alone, deprived of rhythm information, misses a substantial fraction of related tunes, particularly those that have diverged considerably.\n82\tAmong the pairs that do pass pre-filtering, however, PID is a highly accurate classifier.\n83\tROC curves (Fig.\n84\t1 A) show AUC values of 0.99 (TheSession) and 0.97 (Meertens), indicating that once two melodies are similar enough to be flagged as candidates, their pitch identity score reliably distinguishes same-family from different-family pairs.\n85\tTogether these results show that pitch alignment is a useful but incomplete tool: precise when it finds a match, but blind to pairs that have diverged too far.\n86\tSequence-alignment algorithms cannot correctly align melodies.\n87\tSavage et al.\n88\t14 had to manually correct their 328 328 alignments by visual inspection of the original scores to account for rhythmic information.\n89\tWe use their alignments to illustrate why this was necessary, identifying two fundamental problems with pitch-only alignment.\n90\tThe first problem is ambiguity.\n91\tWhen one sequence has more repeated notes than the other, the algorithm must insert a gap somewhere in the run – but without considering rhythm, all insert positions in the expansion are equally valid.\n92\tIn the example in Fig.\n93\t1 B there are five equally-scored locations for the gap in the repeated ’G’ region.\n94\tRhythm immediately resolves which is correct – the gap should be on the second ’G’.\n95\tTo assess the extent of this problem, we try to recreate the human-corrected alignments in 14 using global alignments and many scoring functions.\n96\tThe best-performing scoring function managed to find the correct alignment for 74 % 74\\text{\\,}\\% of pairs.\n97\tHowever, of these, only 13 % 13\\text{\\,}\\% had a single top-scoring alignment, where the ground-truth correct alignment is recovered unambiguously – these pairs only had 1 or 2 gaps, so this appears to work only for very similar tunes.\n98\tThe rest had a median of 9 top-scoring alignments, with some exceeding a thousand candidates.\n99\tThis places a clear limit on accuracy and usefulness, even for highly similar tunes.\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "fa2c8c86-2844-4ac7-abbf-ca6d31e6e24b", "uuid": "106179e9-ed54-4284-8e2b-73289562fc61", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T12:10:42.270Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_lines.txt", "content": "Contrasting statistical patterns in melodic and molecular evolution reveal distinctive constraints in a culturally evolving system.\nReport GitHub Issue × Title: Content selection saved.\nDescribe the issue below: Description: Submit without GitHub Submit in GitHub arXiv is now an independent nonprofit!\nLearn more &times; Back to arXiv Why HTML?\nReport Issue Back to Abstract Download PDF Abstract References License: CC BY-SA 4.0 arXiv:2607.12673v1 [q-bio.PE] 14 Jul 2026 Contrasting statistical patterns in melodic and molecular evolution reveal distinctive constraints in a culturally evolving system.\nJohn M.\nMcBride 1,* W.\nTecumseh Fitch 1,† ( 1 Department of Behavioral and Cognitive Biology, University of Vienna, Vienna, Austria * Correspondence: jmmcbride@protonmail.com † Correspondence: tecumseh.fitch@univie.ac.at ) Abstract Evolved sequences can be used to infer the rules of evolution.\nOrally transmitted folk melodies are evolved sequences whose similarity to protein sequences (one-dimensional, drawn from a limited alphabet) invites application of bioinformatics methods to study cultural evolution.\nA major obstacle is that melodies encode rhythm, which breaks some assumptions of standard sequence-alignment algorithms.\nWe develop a rhythm-aware alignment method and apply it to 40 , 000 40,000 Irish dance tune variants, enabling the first large-scale automated melodic alignment.\nFour canonical bioinformatics analyses – mutability, substitution matrices, positional conservation, and covariance – reveal patterns distinct from those of molecular evolution, revealing the forces that shape each domain: biochemical and biophysical constraints for proteins; memory, motor, and social biases for melodies.\nTogether the results show that bioinformatics provides a powerful framework – conceptual as much as algorithmic – for studying cultural evolution.\nAlthough the cultural transmission of music has been discussed for centuries, here we show how to analyze it at large scale.\nKeywords: cultural evolution | melody | bioinformatics | sequence alignment | Irish folk music ntroduction Sequences generated by evolutionary processes are a wellspring of information that can be used to infer the rules by which they evolved.\nExamples from language span the decoding of ancient languages, 1 to the development of modern language models.\n2 Analysis of biological sequences allows us to infer evolutionary histories, 3 ; 4 the rules of protein biophysics and evolution, 5 ; 6 and to predict future evolutionary trends.\n7 ; 8 Melodies are also sequences that have been shaped and selected through cultural evolution, 9 ; 10 ; 11 ; 12 ; 13 and hold untapped potential for understanding the rules and history of musical evolution, and thus perhaps of cultural evolution more generally.\nAlgorithms offer a clear route to knowledge transfer from bioinformatics.\nMelodies can be represented as 1-dimensional pitch sequences, and sequence alignment tools can in principle be used to compare melodies directly.\n14 ; 15 However, there are noteworthy distinctions both in the form and the evolution of melodic and biological sequences.\nLetters in biological sequences always represent the same chemical unit, while for melodies, notes have two effective dimensions – pitch and rhythm.\nWhen notes are subdivided into multiple shorter notes, or fused into longer notes, alignment algorithms treat this as a ‘gap’, or an insertion/deletion (indel), 16 but this is qualitatively different from the insertions and deletions that arise in biological sequences.\nThese distinctions can at best lead to suboptimal performance when using bioinformatics algorithms out-of-the-box, but could easily lead to major systematic errors.\nKnowledge transfer from bioinformatics is not limited to algorithms, but also broader methodological approaches to discovering the statistical regularities in sets of sequences.\nKey analyses such as amino acid mutability, substitution matrices, sequence conservation and covariance, all led to important discoveries and are foundational to modern bioinformatic analysis.\n17 ; 18 ; 19 ; 20 ; 21 For example, sequence covariance – correlations between substitutions at different positions – can inform us about how a protein folds, 22 such that we can now predict structure given sufficient co-evolutionary information.\n23 ; 24 Here, we propose that bioinformatics analyses can be tailored to melodies, as detailed below, to uncover general rules underlying melodic evolution.\nAs a case study in how to adapt bioinformatics methods for melodies we focus on Irish dance tunes.\nWe chose this tradition for three reasons.\nFolk tunes in general have the right evolutionary properties, dance tunes in particular are methodologically tractable, and Irish music is uniquely well-documented.\nWe now elaborate on each of these reasons.\nFirst, folk tunes persist in recognizable forms over long periods, change to produce variants, and are subject to cultural selection.\n25 ; 26 Change comes from transmission by ear, which introduces copying errors through limits on perception and memory.\n27 ; 11 Intentional variation adds further change, as melodic improvisation is a valued skill in Irish folk music.\n28 These forces – copying fidelity, conformity bias from ensemble playing, and novelty bias from individual expression – produce an ecosystem of tunes and variants, analogous to genes and their homologues, which can be grouped into tune families based on shared melodic history.\n29 ; 10 Second, dance tunes are especially tractable for rhythm-aware sequence analysis.\nAs they are designed for dancing, they obey strict metrical and structural constraints: 30 ; 31 parts have fixed lengths, contain no rests, and can therefore be aligned without gaps – sidestepping one of the central difficulties of sequence alignment.\nTunes also conform to specific tonalities, with pitches drawn from sets of seven or fewer pitch classes.\nFigure 1: Pitch-only and rhythm-aware alignments.\n(A) Receiver operating curve (ROC) and area-under-the-curve (AUC) values for classifying tunes into families using pitch sequences.\n(B) Illustration of two problems with aligning melodies without rhythm information.\nWe show excerpts of two melodies from the Bronson dataset, alongside the manually-corrected pitch sequence alignments.\n14 Without knowledge of rhythm, the alignment to the ’EFF’ part of the lower sequence will always be ’E-F’ or ’EF-’, instead of the correct alignment, ’-EF’.\nThe region with ’GGGGG’ matched to ’G-GGG’ is not a unique solution.\nOther top-scoring alignment solutions include ’-GGGG’, ’GG-GG’, ’GGG-G’, ’GGGG-’.\n(C) An example of a jig (6/8 meter).\nThese are the first two parts of the four-part jig, “The Lark in the Morning”.\nRepeat lines are highlighted with red circles.\nAfter expanding repeats there are 32 measures.\n(D) The same jig (C) represented in the format used for alignments.\nTo get this we expand repeats, map the notes onto a grid with a standard grid size (in this case, eighth notes), and separate tunes into parts.\nFinally, Irish dance tunes stand out for the richness and scale of available data.\nMultiple dance forms and tonalities produce structured variation that is both diverse and constrained – an ideal combination for statistical analysis.\nThis tradition is also unusually well-documented online, owing in part to the ABC notation format developed in 1994, 32 which made sharing tune transcriptions easy and led to repositories including (but not limited to) thesession.org, which holds over 50 , 000 50,000 community-contributed tunes.\n33 ; 34 ; 35 ; 36 The total number of tunes and variants available in digital form online exceeds 100 , 000 100,000 , a uniquely large dataset.\nThe concept of tune evolution and tune families has been developed over many years, 9 ; 10 ; 37 ; 38 but empirical research on how melodies evolve remains in its infancy.\n14 ; 15 ; 39 ; 40 ; 41 ; 42 Previous efforts involving manual comparison of similar tunes, 43 ; 26 ; 44 ; 45 are not scalable to large datasets.\nAs for computational approaches, most have been dealing with orthogonal topics such as tune family identification, 46 ; 47 ; 48 ; 49 ; 50 or phylogeny.\n51 ; 52 ; 53 In a seminal contribution, Savage et al.\n14 used sequence analysis tools for similar tune identification.\nThey did attempt using bioinformatics tools to align sequences, but due to poor quality of automated alignments had to manually align their sequences.\nThus they compared only 328 328 pairs of tunes, several orders of magnitude lower than the number in principle permitted for a joint collection numbering 10 , 000 10,000 melodies.\nFurthermore, the melodies were encoded in a reduced format that excluded most rhythmic, and some melodic information.\nThus, compared to what has been discovered in biology or linguistics, existing studies on melody evolution have only scratched the surface of what is possible in theory.\nHere, we first show that bioinformatics algorithms are useful for identifying similar tune variants, but not for aligning them.\nWe develop a novel rhythm-aware alignment method suitable for musical traditions with rigid metrical structure.\nApplying it to 40 , 000 40,000 Irish dance tune variants, we run four canonical bioinformatics analyses (mutability, substitution matrices, positional conservation, and covariance) and show that the resulting statistical signatures highlight clear differences between molecular and melodic sequence evolution.\nWe then use the results to devise hypotheses and analyses designed to uncover the constraints that guide melodic evolutionary paths.\nThe analyses reveal statistical signatures that are categorically different from those of protein evolution.\nIn particular, we find that pitch mutability tracks tonal hierarchy, reflecting memory and perceptual constraints on transmission; substitution rates mirror the melodic interval distribution, reflecting motor constraints on melodic motion; positional conservation correlates with metrical hierarchy, and covariance reveals conserved repetition structure.\nThe last two findings are consistent with the long-standing hypothesis that a stable “melodic skeleton” encodes tune identity 30 , and we outline experimental predictions that would test it.\nesults Is pitch sufficient to identify similar melodies?\nDo pitch sequences, without any rhythm or note durations, contain sufficient information for identifying similar melodies?\nIf you attend an Irish traditional music session you can see participants, if they do not know the tune that is being played, using an app – TunePal, 54 or FolkFriend 55 – to query the tune.\nThese apps work well, but their algorithms use both pitch and rhythm.\n56 Whether pitch alone is sufficient has been sporadically investigated with no clear consensus.\nOne study found moderate success on 6 , 000 6,000 Dutch songs, 46 while others used small sample sizes 48 ; 49 or non-standard evaluation metrics.\n14 ; 57 We tested this using the standard algorithm MMseqs2 58 on two large datasets (TheSession, Meertens), amounting to billions of tune comparisons.\nThe algorithm first eliminates pairs that are unlikely to match, then computes percent identity ( PID ) scores – a measure of sequence similarity – for the remainder using local alignment.\nThe overall true positive rates – including pairs eliminated at the pre-filtering stage – were 0.71 (TheSession) and 0.42 (Meertens).\nThus pitch alignment alone, deprived of rhythm information, misses a substantial fraction of related tunes, particularly those that have diverged considerably.\nAmong the pairs that do pass pre-filtering, however, PID is a highly accurate classifier.\nROC curves (Fig.\n1 A) show AUC values of 0.99 (TheSession) and 0.97 (Meertens), indicating that once two melodies are similar enough to be flagged as candidates, their pitch identity score reliably distinguishes same-family from different-family pairs.\nTogether these results show that pitch alignment is a useful but incomplete tool: precise when it finds a match, but blind to pairs that have diverged too far.\nSequence-alignment algorithms cannot correctly align melodies.\nSavage et al.\n14 had to manually correct their 328 328 alignments by visual inspection of the original scores to account for rhythmic information.\nWe use their alignments to illustrate why this was necessary, identifying two fundamental problems with pitch-only alignment.\nThe first problem is ambiguity.\nWhen one sequence has more repeated notes than the other, the algorithm must insert a gap somewhere in the run – but without considering rhythm, all insert positions in the expansion are equally valid.\nIn the example in Fig.\n1 B there are five equally-scored locations for the gap in the repeated ’G’ region.\nRhythm immediately resolves which is correct – the gap should be on the second ’G’.\nTo assess the extent of this problem, we try to recreate the human-corrected alignments in 14 using global alignments and many scoring functions.\nThe best-performing scoring function managed to find the correct alignment for 74 % 74\\text{\\,}\\% of pairs.\nHowever, of these, only 13 % 13\\text{\\,}\\% had a single top-scoring alignment, where the ground-truth correct alignment is recovered unambiguously – these pairs only had 1 or 2 gaps, so this appears to work only for very similar tunes.\nThe rest had a median of 9 top-scoring alignments, with some exceeding a thousand candidates.\nThis places a clear limit on accuracy and usefulness, even for highly similar tunes.", "numLines": 100, "startLine": 0, "totalLines": 1272}}}
