{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-939c9654910f20bc", "type": "tool_result", "content": "100\tThis places a clear limit on accuracy and usefulness, even for highly similar tunes.\n101\tThe second problem is more pernicious: some correct alignments are unreachable by any pitch-only algorithm.\n102\tIn Fig.\n103\t1 B, “CEF” in the top melody corresponds to “CEFF” in the bottom melody.\n104\tA quarter-note ‘C’ in the top sequence corresponds to two eighth notes ‘C’ and ‘E’ in the bottom – the note subdivision leads to a gap.\n105\tThe correct answer, given the rhythm, is to insert the gap after the ‘C’ to align the pitch-mismatched ‘E’ and ‘F’: “C-EF”.\n106\tA pitch-only alignment will always align the two ‘E’ notes and place the gap on the ‘F’: “CE-F”.\n107\tThis is why for 17 % 17\\text{\\,}\\% of pairs, the ground-truth alignment did not achieve a top score, regardless of the scoring function used.\n108\tGenerally, alignment on pitches alone will lead to systematic undercounting of pitch substitutions.\n109\tFigure 2: Comparing molecular and melodic evolution.\n110\t(A) Amino acid mutability (relative to alanine) and prevalence; 59 C (cysteine), W (tryptophan) and L (leucine) are highlighted.\n111\t(B) Pitch mutability and prevalence ( PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$85\\text{\\,}\\%$ ) in Irish traditional music; C (tonic), G (dominant) and C# are highlighted.\n112\t(C–D) Substitution matrices (lower triangle; log-odds of observed to expected substitution rate) for amino acids (C; BLOSUM62) and pitches (D; Major scale, PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$85\\text{\\,}\\%$ ).\n113\tAmino acids are ordered by chemical similarity according to the Dayhoff classification scheme (C; black squares).\n114\t(E–F, top) Sequence conservation along cytochrome c (P00004) and the melody “Man of the House” (first part); red indicates conserved positions, blue indicates variable positions.\n115\tVertical lines mark every eighth position.\n116\t(E, bottom) Per-position substitution rate versus structural exposure (relative solvent accessibility) for cytochrome c.\n117\t(F, bottom) Per-position substitution rate versus rhythmic strength (probability of a note onset at that metric position), both normalised by the per-meter mean, for five meters (4/4, 6/8, 2/4, 9/8, 12/8; PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$85\\text{\\,}\\%$ ).\n118\tThe final position of each measure is circled.\n119\t(G) Structure of thioredoxin (P0AA25) depicted as a C α \\alpha contact map – positions are considered in contact (black) if they are within 0.8 nm 0.8\\text{\\,}\\mathrm{n}\\mathrm{m} in the folded structure.\n120\tA parallel β \\beta -strand structural element is highlighted in red.\n121\t(H) Position-position covariance for 4/4 tunes ( PID ≥ 50 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$50\\text{\\,}\\%$ ).\n122\tRhythm-aware alignment of tune parts.\n123\tThe dance tunes in TheSession follow strict rules governing meter and structure, where tunes are composed of parts of either 8 or 16 measures with a regular meter.\n124\tFor example, the jig “The Lark in the Morning” is a four part jig (6/8) composed of four parts of 8 measures each, that are each repeated once (Fig.\n125\t1 C; only two parts are shown).\n126\tWe separated tunes into their parts (see Dividing Tunes into Parts), and quantize the pitches onto a regular grid (Fig.\n127\t1 D; see Melodic Sequence Representations) which makes it easy to align using note and measure onsets.\n128\tOur pipeline ultimately produced 51 , 680 51,680 pairs of similar parts from 41 , 050 41,050 tunes (see Rhythm-Aware Part Alignment).\n129\tComparing molecular and melodic sequence evolution With this alignment method in place, we now adapt four canonical bioinformatics analyses – mutability, substitution matrices, positional conservation, and covariance – to compare the statistical signatures of molecular and melodic evolution.\n130\tThese analyses underpin much of what is known about protein evolution, and together form the historic backbone of the field.\n131\tThe protein panels in Fig.\n132\t2 are chosen as familiar illustrative examples of phenomena that have been established across thousands of protein families; 17 ; 18 ; 5 ; 60 our focus is on whether analogous statistical signatures exist in melodies, and whether melodic evolution follows the same pattern.\n133\tMutability.\n134\tAmino acids vary at different rates.\n135\tBy aligning closely related protein sequences and counting the occurrences and substitutions across variants, Dayhoff et al.\n136\t17 obtained a measure of mutability – the substitution rate divided by the occurrence rate.\n137\tDifferences in mutability reflect the functional importance of each amino acid and are shaped by biochemistry.\n138\tFor example, cysteine is not easily replaced as it is the only amino acid with a reactive sulphur, essential for both structure (disulphide bonds) and catalytic function.\n139\t61 A side-by-side comparison of mutability against prevalence in the two domains reveals a sharp asymmetry (Fig.\n140\t2 A,B).\n141\tFor amino acids the correlation is weakly positive and non-significant ( r = 0.30 r=0.30 , p = 0.2 p=0.2 ).\n142\tFor pitches we see an exceptionally strong negative relationship ( r = − 0.95 r=-0.95 ): more prevalent notes are less likely to mutate.\n143\tThis correlation is robust, holding when tune parts are analysed separately by mode (Supplementary Fig.\n144\t2).\n145\tThe tonic (C) and dominant (G) are the most stable, while the rarest notes are the most readily substituted; for tunes in Dorian mode, the most mutable note (minor 6th) is more than twice as mutable as the least mutable note (tonic).\n146\tNo simple correlation emerges for amino acids because the prevalence and mutability of each amino acid are governed by several independent factors.\n147\tTryptophan is rare because it is metabolically costly to synthesise; cysteine is rare because its reactive sulphur is potentially hazardous; leucine is common because it plays a structural role in protein cores.\n148\tEach amino acid is affected by functional, structural, and biosynthetic constraints, and no single axis dominates.\n149\tPitches, by contrast, are not as multi-faceted, and their mutability is free to follow the single underlying dimension of note frequency in Hz.\n150\tSubstitution matrices.\n151\tNext we ask which pairs of elements are interchangeable.\n152\tSubstitution matrices count co-occurrence – how often each pair of letters co-occurs at the same position across many aligned sequence pairs, normalised by each element’s baseline frequency to give a log-odds score.\n153\t18 Positive values indicate pairs that substitute more often than expected by chance, and negative values the opposite.\n154\tThe most widely used protein matrix, BLOSUM62, reveals clusters of chemically, and hence functionally, similar amino acids – e.g.\n155\t, hydrophobic amino acids exchange with other hydrophobic amino acids (Fig.\n156\t2 C).\n157\tWe computed an analogous matrix for pitch sequences in Major-mode tune parts (Fig.\n158\t2 D, see Supplementary Fig.\n159\t3 for other modes).\n160\tA similar analysis was performed by Savage et al.\n161\t14 , but with important and consequential methodological differences (see Supplementary Section 5).\n162\tFor pitch as well as amino acids, elements cluster by similarity, but the clustering pattern is different.\n163\tFor pitch, the similarity metric that emerges is not chemistry but interval size : the highest log-odds scores lie close to (or far from, since pitch class structure is circular) the diagonal, meaning that pitches preferentially substitute for their scalar near-neighbours.\n164\tBoth domains therefore produce substitution matrices that group elements by functional similarity; they differ only on what dimension defines “similar”.\n165\tPositional conservation.\n166\tEvolutionary rates also vary along the length of a sequence: some positions are far more conserved than others.\n167\tIn proteins, this is because amino acids at structurally or functionally critical positions ( e.g.\n168\t, catalytic sites in enzymes) cannot be easily replaced.\n169\tStructurally, amino acids buried in the folded core cannot tolerate substitutions that would disrupt packing, while surface-exposed positions are freer to change.\n170\t5 Fig.\n171\t2 E illustrates this with cytochrome c: position-by-position conservation is shown on top, and per-position substitution rate against relative solvent accessibility – the fraction of an amino acid’s surface that is exposed – on the bottom.\n172\tMelodic positions also vary systematically in conservation, but for a very different reason.\n173\tFig.\n174\t2 F shows conservation along the first part of “Man of the House” (top), and per-position substitution rate plotted against rhythmic strength – the empirical probability that a note onset falls on a given metric position – pooled across five meters (bottom).\n175\tPositions of high rhythmic strength are the most conserved; those at the end of each measure are the least.\n176\tWhereas for proteins structure is spatial (3D), for melodies it is temporal – where a position sits in the metrical cycle.\n177\tThis distinction leaves a striking visual signature in the conservation strips at the top of Fig.\n178\t2 E,F.\n179\tFor cytochrome c, conserved and variable positions are scattered along the sequence with no apparent pattern or periodicity, because the seqeuence order becomes decorrelated from spatial order for positions that are further apart.\n180\tFor “Man of the House” the strip is visibly regular, with conserved positions lining up at periodic intervals, because here the linear order of the sequence is the structural order: the metrical cycle unfolds along the axis of the plot, and any regularity in that cycle shows up directly as regularity in conservation/variability.\n181\tCovariance.\n182\tThe fourth analysis looks not at individual positions but at correlated substitutions between pairs of positions.\n183\tIn proteins, covariance is a window onto 3D structure: two sequence positions that are distant along the linear chain, but brought into contact by folding, co-evolve to preserve that contact.\n184\tThe signal is rich enough that sequence covariance, with appropriate statistical treatment, can recover a protein’s 3D contact map, and is now a central ingredient in protein structure prediction.\n185\t60 ; 23 We display the two analyses in complementary forms.\n186\tFig.\n187\t2 G shows the C α contact map of thioredoxin – the physical structure that protein covariance analysis is used to reconstruct – with a parallel β \\beta -strand highlighted as a line parallel to the diagonal.\n188\tMelodies do not fold in three dimensions and have no analogous structural ground truth; we therefore show the position-position covariance matrix for 4/4 tune parts directly (Fig.\n189\t2 H), computed over the first eight measures.\n190\tBoth short- and long-range structure are present, and the long-range component is strikingly periodic, at integer multiples of one measure.\n191\tThis is visible as bands parallel to the diagonal, reminiscent of the β \\beta -strand signature in the protein covariance matrix.\n192\tWe conjecture that this periodicity arises from repetition itself: whenever a motif recurs within a tune, its repeated positions become evolutionarily correlated.\n193\tChanges to the melody thus tend to be repeated when replayed later in the tune.\n194\tFigure 3: Exploring hypotheses for the rules of melodic evolution.\n195\t(A) Key-finding accuracy using the first N N eighth notes selected by position in the melody (‘First Notes’), or by within-family substitution rate (‘Most Conserved Notes’ and ‘Least Conserved Notes’).\n196\tEvaluated on tune families with at least 10 10 alignment pairs.\n197\t(B) Absolute substitution rate versus intervallic distance (coloured lines) alongside the melodic interval probability distribution for TheSession (black line).\n198\tAll curves are normalised by their sum for ease of comparison.\n199\tBronson and Japanese data from 14 ; TheSession rates for pairs with PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$85\\text{\\,}\\%$ .\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "fa2c8c86-2844-4ac7-abbf-ca6d31e6e24b", "uuid": "d5880d28-de51-44a4-9037-2414bbdebb46", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T12:10:57.056Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_lines.txt", "content": "This places a clear limit on accuracy and usefulness, even for highly similar tunes.\nThe second problem is more pernicious: some correct alignments are unreachable by any pitch-only algorithm.\nIn Fig.\n1 B, “CEF” in the top melody corresponds to “CEFF” in the bottom melody.\nA quarter-note ‘C’ in the top sequence corresponds to two eighth notes ‘C’ and ‘E’ in the bottom – the note subdivision leads to a gap.\nThe correct answer, given the rhythm, is to insert the gap after the ‘C’ to align the pitch-mismatched ‘E’ and ‘F’: “C-EF”.\nA pitch-only alignment will always align the two ‘E’ notes and place the gap on the ‘F’: “CE-F”.\nThis is why for 17 % 17\\text{\\,}\\% of pairs, the ground-truth alignment did not achieve a top score, regardless of the scoring function used.\nGenerally, alignment on pitches alone will lead to systematic undercounting of pitch substitutions.\nFigure 2: Comparing molecular and melodic evolution.\n(A) Amino acid mutability (relative to alanine) and prevalence; 59 C (cysteine), W (tryptophan) and L (leucine) are highlighted.\n(B) Pitch mutability and prevalence ( PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$85\\text{\\,}\\%$ ) in Irish traditional music; C (tonic), G (dominant) and C# are highlighted.\n(C–D) Substitution matrices (lower triangle; log-odds of observed to expected substitution rate) for amino acids (C; BLOSUM62) and pitches (D; Major scale, PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$85\\text{\\,}\\%$ ).\nAmino acids are ordered by chemical similarity according to the Dayhoff classification scheme (C; black squares).\n(E–F, top) Sequence conservation along cytochrome c (P00004) and the melody “Man of the House” (first part); red indicates conserved positions, blue indicates variable positions.\nVertical lines mark every eighth position.\n(E, bottom) Per-position substitution rate versus structural exposure (relative solvent accessibility) for cytochrome c.\n(F, bottom) Per-position substitution rate versus rhythmic strength (probability of a note onset at that metric position), both normalised by the per-meter mean, for five meters (4/4, 6/8, 2/4, 9/8, 12/8; PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$85\\text{\\,}\\%$ ).\nThe final position of each measure is circled.\n(G) Structure of thioredoxin (P0AA25) depicted as a C α \\alpha contact map – positions are considered in contact (black) if they are within 0.8 nm 0.8\\text{\\,}\\mathrm{n}\\mathrm{m} in the folded structure.\nA parallel β \\beta -strand structural element is highlighted in red.\n(H) Position-position covariance for 4/4 tunes ( PID ≥ 50 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$50\\text{\\,}\\%$ ).\nRhythm-aware alignment of tune parts.\nThe dance tunes in TheSession follow strict rules governing meter and structure, where tunes are composed of parts of either 8 or 16 measures with a regular meter.\nFor example, the jig “The Lark in the Morning” is a four part jig (6/8) composed of four parts of 8 measures each, that are each repeated once (Fig.\n1 C; only two parts are shown).\nWe separated tunes into their parts (see Dividing Tunes into Parts), and quantize the pitches onto a regular grid (Fig.\n1 D; see Melodic Sequence Representations) which makes it easy to align using note and measure onsets.\nOur pipeline ultimately produced 51 , 680 51,680 pairs of similar parts from 41 , 050 41,050 tunes (see Rhythm-Aware Part Alignment).\nComparing molecular and melodic sequence evolution With this alignment method in place, we now adapt four canonical bioinformatics analyses – mutability, substitution matrices, positional conservation, and covariance – to compare the statistical signatures of molecular and melodic evolution.\nThese analyses underpin much of what is known about protein evolution, and together form the historic backbone of the field.\nThe protein panels in Fig.\n2 are chosen as familiar illustrative examples of phenomena that have been established across thousands of protein families; 17 ; 18 ; 5 ; 60 our focus is on whether analogous statistical signatures exist in melodies, and whether melodic evolution follows the same pattern.\nMutability.\nAmino acids vary at different rates.\nBy aligning closely related protein sequences and counting the occurrences and substitutions across variants, Dayhoff et al.\n17 obtained a measure of mutability – the substitution rate divided by the occurrence rate.\nDifferences in mutability reflect the functional importance of each amino acid and are shaped by biochemistry.\nFor example, cysteine is not easily replaced as it is the only amino acid with a reactive sulphur, essential for both structure (disulphide bonds) and catalytic function.\n61 A side-by-side comparison of mutability against prevalence in the two domains reveals a sharp asymmetry (Fig.\n2 A,B).\nFor amino acids the correlation is weakly positive and non-significant ( r = 0.30 r=0.30 , p = 0.2 p=0.2 ).\nFor pitches we see an exceptionally strong negative relationship ( r = − 0.95 r=-0.95 ): more prevalent notes are less likely to mutate.\nThis correlation is robust, holding when tune parts are analysed separately by mode (Supplementary Fig.\n2).\nThe tonic (C) and dominant (G) are the most stable, while the rarest notes are the most readily substituted; for tunes in Dorian mode, the most mutable note (minor 6th) is more than twice as mutable as the least mutable note (tonic).\nNo simple correlation emerges for amino acids because the prevalence and mutability of each amino acid are governed by several independent factors.\nTryptophan is rare because it is metabolically costly to synthesise; cysteine is rare because its reactive sulphur is potentially hazardous; leucine is common because it plays a structural role in protein cores.\nEach amino acid is affected by functional, structural, and biosynthetic constraints, and no single axis dominates.\nPitches, by contrast, are not as multi-faceted, and their mutability is free to follow the single underlying dimension of note frequency in Hz.\nSubstitution matrices.\nNext we ask which pairs of elements are interchangeable.\nSubstitution matrices count co-occurrence – how often each pair of letters co-occurs at the same position across many aligned sequence pairs, normalised by each element’s baseline frequency to give a log-odds score.\n18 Positive values indicate pairs that substitute more often than expected by chance, and negative values the opposite.\nThe most widely used protein matrix, BLOSUM62, reveals clusters of chemically, and hence functionally, similar amino acids – e.g.\n, hydrophobic amino acids exchange with other hydrophobic amino acids (Fig.\n2 C).\nWe computed an analogous matrix for pitch sequences in Major-mode tune parts (Fig.\n2 D, see Supplementary Fig.\n3 for other modes).\nA similar analysis was performed by Savage et al.\n14 , but with important and consequential methodological differences (see Supplementary Section 5).\nFor pitch as well as amino acids, elements cluster by similarity, but the clustering pattern is different.\nFor pitch, the similarity metric that emerges is not chemistry but interval size : the highest log-odds scores lie close to (or far from, since pitch class structure is circular) the diagonal, meaning that pitches preferentially substitute for their scalar near-neighbours.\nBoth domains therefore produce substitution matrices that group elements by functional similarity; they differ only on what dimension defines “similar”.\nPositional conservation.\nEvolutionary rates also vary along the length of a sequence: some positions are far more conserved than others.\nIn proteins, this is because amino acids at structurally or functionally critical positions ( e.g.\n, catalytic sites in enzymes) cannot be easily replaced.\nStructurally, amino acids buried in the folded core cannot tolerate substitutions that would disrupt packing, while surface-exposed positions are freer to change.\n5 Fig.\n2 E illustrates this with cytochrome c: position-by-position conservation is shown on top, and per-position substitution rate against relative solvent accessibility – the fraction of an amino acid’s surface that is exposed – on the bottom.\nMelodic positions also vary systematically in conservation, but for a very different reason.\nFig.\n2 F shows conservation along the first part of “Man of the House” (top), and per-position substitution rate plotted against rhythmic strength – the empirical probability that a note onset falls on a given metric position – pooled across five meters (bottom).\nPositions of high rhythmic strength are the most conserved; those at the end of each measure are the least.\nWhereas for proteins structure is spatial (3D), for melodies it is temporal – where a position sits in the metrical cycle.\nThis distinction leaves a striking visual signature in the conservation strips at the top of Fig.\n2 E,F.\nFor cytochrome c, conserved and variable positions are scattered along the sequence with no apparent pattern or periodicity, because the seqeuence order becomes decorrelated from spatial order for positions that are further apart.\nFor “Man of the House” the strip is visibly regular, with conserved positions lining up at periodic intervals, because here the linear order of the sequence is the structural order: the metrical cycle unfolds along the axis of the plot, and any regularity in that cycle shows up directly as regularity in conservation/variability.\nCovariance.\nThe fourth analysis looks not at individual positions but at correlated substitutions between pairs of positions.\nIn proteins, covariance is a window onto 3D structure: two sequence positions that are distant along the linear chain, but brought into contact by folding, co-evolve to preserve that contact.\nThe signal is rich enough that sequence covariance, with appropriate statistical treatment, can recover a protein’s 3D contact map, and is now a central ingredient in protein structure prediction.\n60 ; 23 We display the two analyses in complementary forms.\nFig.\n2 G shows the C α contact map of thioredoxin – the physical structure that protein covariance analysis is used to reconstruct – with a parallel β \\beta -strand highlighted as a line parallel to the diagonal.\nMelodies do not fold in three dimensions and have no analogous structural ground truth; we therefore show the position-position covariance matrix for 4/4 tune parts directly (Fig.\n2 H), computed over the first eight measures.\nBoth short- and long-range structure are present, and the long-range component is strikingly periodic, at integer multiples of one measure.\nThis is visible as bands parallel to the diagonal, reminiscent of the β \\beta -strand signature in the protein covariance matrix.\nWe conjecture that this periodicity arises from repetition itself: whenever a motif recurs within a tune, its repeated positions become evolutionarily correlated.\nChanges to the melody thus tend to be repeated when replayed later in the tune.\nFigure 3: Exploring hypotheses for the rules of melodic evolution.\n(A) Key-finding accuracy using the first N N eighth notes selected by position in the melody (‘First Notes’), or by within-family substitution rate (‘Most Conserved Notes’ and ‘Least Conserved Notes’).\nEvaluated on tune families with at least 10 10 alignment pairs.\n(B) Absolute substitution rate versus intervallic distance (coloured lines) alongside the melodic interval probability distribution for TheSession (black line).\nAll curves are normalised by their sum for ease of comparison.\nBronson and Japanese data from 14 ; TheSession rates for pairs with PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$85\\text{\\,}\\%$ .", "numLines": 100, "startLine": 100, "totalLines": 1272}}}
