{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a2909fdfa54ac1c1", "type": "tool_result", "content": "200\t(C) Log-odds score (log-odds of observed to expected rate) versus intervallic distance ( PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$85\\text{\\,}\\%$ ).\n201\tGrey line and shaded region show a linear fit with 95 % 95\\text{\\,}\\% confidence interval (Pearson’s r = − 0.82 r=-0.82 , p = 0.001 p=0.001 , n = 13 n=13 ).\n202\t(D) Substitution rate at each eighth-note position within a 6/8 measure, coloured by metrical hierarchy.\n203\tError bars show bootstrapped 95 % 95\\text{\\,}\\% confidence intervals.\n204\t(E) Normalised substitution rate versus metrical hierarchy, pooled across five meters (4/4, 6/8, 2/4, 9/8, 12/8), coloured by meter ( r = 0.71 r=0.71 , p = 4.8 × 10 − 7 p=4.8\\times 10^{-7} ).\n205\t(F) Position-position covariance matrix, Σ i ​ j \\Sigma_{ij} , for all 6/8 tune pairs ( PID ≥ 50 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$50\\text{\\,}\\%$ ).\n206\t(G) Repetition covariance for the same pairs: the component of Σ i ​ j \\Sigma_{ij} arising from position pairs linked by within-tune pitch repetition in both sequences.\n207\tExplanations for these patterns Having shown that comparable analyses can be robustly performed on protein sequences and melodies, producing meaningful but different results, we now turn to testing exploratory hypotheses that attempt to explain these patterns.\n208\tConserved notes are more useful for key-finding.\n209\tThe strong correlation between pitch mutability and prevalence (Fig.\n210\t2 B) begs an explanation.\n211\tOne candidate is key and mode identification: prevalent notes may be those most useful for establishing a tune’s tonality, which in turn constrains the set of likely pitches and thereby facilitates recognition, learning, and memory.\n212\tThis hypothesis predicts that the stable notes will be the most informative about tonality.\n213\tFor an exploratory test, we develop a key-finding algorithm trained on TheSession collection (see Key Estimation), and evaluate it by estimating the key from only the first N N notes of each tune (Fig.\n214\t3 A).\n215\tThe algorithm achieves about 65 % 65\\text{\\,}\\% accuracy using only the first 10 10 notes.\n216\tThis is well above chance ( 12.5 % 12.5\\text{\\,}\\% ), and it may be close to the practical limit, since tonality is not strictly established in many Irish tunes, which was historically practised without harmonic accompaniment.\n217\tWe then apply this algorithm to the N N most- and least-conserved note positions within tune families ( PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$85\\text{\\,}\\%$ ).\n218\tThe most-conserved notes are substantially more useful in key determination than the least-conserved notes (Fig.\n219\t3 A), with a difference in accuracy of 34 % 34\\text{\\,}\\% at N = 10 N=10 , which persists even beyond N = 50 N=50 .\n220\tThis shows that evolutionarily stable notes carry disproportionate information about the tonal identity of a tune.\n221\tKey-finding is functionally useful because knowledge of key and mode constrains the set of likely pitches, making melodies easier to predict and perceive.\n222\tWe can see this reflected in the data by looking at entropy, an information-theoretic measure of complexity 62 .\n223\tPitch class entropy across the full dataset is 3.05 bits, falling to 2.75 bits when tunes are considered within individual keys and modes – a 10 % 10\\text{\\,}\\% reduction.\n224\tStable notes thus appear to help achieve cognitive economy, and their stability may be maintained by selection pressure on learnability and memorability.\n225\tSubstitution distances are constrained by melodic motion.\n226\tThe pitch substitution matrix (Fig.\n227\t2 D) showed clustering along the scalar diagonal, hinting that interval size is the relevant similarity metric for pitch substitution.\n228\tOne candidate explanation is that the motor constraints governing melodic motion also govern which notes substitute, so that substitutions are limited to those that maintain the melodic style.\n229\tUnlike amino acids, pitches have a natural, one-dimensional similarity metric, so we can measure substitution rate as a continuous function of intervallic distance and test this directly.\n230\tIt also lets us probe whether octave equivalence, the perceptual tendency to hear pitches an octave apart as similar, 63 plays a role.\n231\tWe first measure absolute substitution rate as a function of intervallic distance for TheSession tune parts ( PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$85\\text{\\,}\\%$ ), since this is what was previously calculated for the Bronson and Japanese collections.\n232\t14 We divided each rate curve by its integral to aid visual comparison (Fig.\n233\t3 B).\n234\tHere we can see similarities between the three collections.\n235\tThe most notable difference is that TheSession tunes have much higher note-substitution rates at large intervallic distances (7 and 12 semitones) than found previously.\n236\tThis perhaps reflects different constraints on melodic evolution in vocal (Bronson and Japanese) vs instrumental (TheSession) music.\n237\tThe instrumental tunes often contain melodic passages that follow arpeggiated (3, 4, 5 or 7 semitones) rather than scalar motion (1 or 2 semitones), presumably because the motor constraints are much weaker for instruments.\n238\tCrucially, the substitution rate closely mirrors the overall melodic interval distribution (Pearson’s r = 0.98 r=0.98 , p &lt; 10 − 8 p&lt;10^{-8} , n = 13 n=13 ): substitutions tend to span the same intervals that are prevalent in the style.\n239\tArpeggiated passages are particularly prone to substitution, since the harmonically equivalent notes of a triad are all plausible alternatives; scalar passages in contrast typically move in a clear direction, limiting available options for variation.\n240\tNormalising by the expected rate – i.e.\n241\t, accounting for expectations due to scalar structure – (Fig.\n242\t3 C) makes the dominant trend stark: substitution rate decreases log-linearly with intervallic distance, falling by approximately 20 % 20\\text{\\,}\\% per semitone.\n243\tTwo deviations stand out – tritone substitutions (6 semitones) are rarer than expected; while octave substitutions (12 semitones) are much more common – consistent with spectral similarity and octave equivalence as alternate dimensions of pitch similarity.\n244\tMetrical hierarchy generalises across meters.\n245\tThe pooled relationship in Fig.\n246\t2 F uses rhythmic strength – the empirical probability of a note onset at each metric position – as a data-driven proxy for metrical hierarchy.\n247\tWe now highlight this relationship further using expert-annotated metrical strength – an indicator of how strongly notes at metric positions are accentuated by performers.\n248\tWithin 6/8 tunes, substitution rates vary systematically with position, in a pattern that closely follows metrical hierarchy (Fig.\n249\t3 D; other meters in Supplementary Fig.\n250\t5).\n251\tNotes on metrically strong positions are the most stable, and notes at the end of each measure the most mutable.\n252\tWhen we pool across the five main meters and regress substitution rate against expert-annotated metrical hierarchy, the correlation remains strong (Pearson’s r = 0.71 r=0.71 , p = 4.8 × 10 − 7 p=4.8\\times 10^{-7} ; Fig.\n253\t3 E), replicating and extending a similar finding in Savage et al.\n254\t14 .\n255\tWhy should metrical strength predict stability at all?\n256\tSubstituting a pitch on a strong beat would not disrupt the meter itself, so the pattern cannot be reduced to a rhythmic constraint.\n257\tInstead, these results are consistent with the hypothesis that metrically strong positions collectively form a stable “melodic skeleton” 30 that encodes tune identity and keeps variants mutually compatible in ensemble performance.\n258\tLong-ranged covariance is due to repetition.\n259\tThe short-range covariance visible in Fig.\n260\t2 H reflects the constraint on scalar motion identified above (Fig.\n261\t3 C): neighbouring pitches tend to move together to maintain melodic motion.\n262\tFor the long-range periodicities, we hypothesised that they reflect repetition within the tune: motifs that recur at fixed metrical distances will naturally generate periodic correlations between their positions.\n263\tTo test this, we compute a repetition-specific covariance matrix (see Covariance and Repetition) that isolates the component of covariance arising from within-tune pitch repetition.\n264\tFig.\n265\t3 F shows the full position-position covariance for 6/8 tunes (analogous to Fig.\n266\t2 H for 4/4 tunes), and Fig.\n267\t3 G the corresponding repetition component.\n268\tThe repetition-only matrix reproduces the periodicities of the full matrix, confirming that long-range covariance is consistent with the cyclical repetition structure of the tune.\n269\tThe need to preserve the structure and degree of repetition across variants therefore constrains how these melodies can evolve.\n270\tiscussion Proteins and melodies differ fundamentally because melodies have rhythm – a hierarchical feature with no molecular counterpart.\n271\tThis difference hinders the transfer of bioinformatics methods to music, since standard alignment algorithms cannot appropriately represent the subdivision and fusion of notes.\n272\tHowever, once we solved the alignment problem for highly-structured melodies, the rest of the standard bioinformatics toolkit transferred cleanly.\n273\tEach of the four canonical analyses uncovers clear statistical regularities in both molecular and melodic evolution, but the patterns are categorically different between the two domains.\n274\tThose differences are informative about the evolutionary forces that shape each: biochemical and biophysical constraints for proteins; social transmission and individual cognitive and motor biases for melodies.\n275\tThe combination of these forces makes melodies a promising model system for understanding the interplay of these cognitive factors in cultural evolution.\n276\tHypothesis: cognitive and motor biases shape melodic variation.\n277\tTwo of our findings suggest independent transmission biases at the level of the individual learner.\n278\tEvolutionary stability tracks tonal hierarchy: the tonic and dominant (‘C’ and ‘G’ in the key of C) are the most stable pitch classes, while the least stable are those absent from specific modes (Fig.\n279\t2 B).\n280\tThis contrasts with amino acids, where prevalence and stability reflect a mix of functional, structural, and biosynthetic factors.\n281\tA simple hypothesis is that stable notes are those most useful for establishing key and mode, since a clear sense of tonality reduces the information burden on performers and facilitates predictive coding, learning and memory.\n282\tOur key-finding analysis supports this: the most evolutionarily stable notes are the most informative for key estimation, consistent with predictive cognitive constraints on cultural transmission (Fig.\n283\t3 A).\n284\tThe two components of this hypothesis – stable notes are good for key-finding, knowledge of a key improves learning and memory – can be directly tested with cognitive experiments.\n285\tAn alternate hypothesis is that both prevalence and stability are both products of a third component, such as a cultural attractor towards certain pitches.\n286\tMotor constraints leave a separate signature in the substitution pattern.\n287\tSubstitution rates mirror the melodic interval distribution of each style (Fig.\n288\t3 B, r = 0.98 r=0.98 ), meaning that substitutions tend to span the same intervals that are common in normal melodic motion.\n289\tThe higher rates of substitutions at large arpeggiated intervals (5 or 7 semitones) in TheSession compared to vocal collections likely reflect weaker motor constraints on large pitch jumps on instruments than for the voice – a fiddle or flute can leap more easily than a singer.\n290\tA direct test would be to compare substitution matrices across traditions differing systematically in instrumental versus vocal performance.\n291\tThe vocal-instrumental dichotomy can be broadened to include the fact that different instruments lead to different constraints – single-string chordophones should exhibit more similar behaviour to the voice compared to multi-string chordophones, where large intervals are facilitated by strings tuned to different pitches.\n292\tHypothesis: a stable melodic skeleton encodes tune identity.\n293\tPitch variation is organised along a temporal hierarchy, both at the within-measure metrical level (Fig.\n294\t3 E), and the between-measure level where repetition is clearly structured (Fig.\n295\t3 G).\n296\tMetrical hierarchy itself has an obvious functional basis in dance – strong beats are marked by higher onset probability, and this rhythmic regularity is what makes the beat perceptible and the tune danceable.\n297\tBut this explains only the rhythm, not the pitch; nothing about the metrical constraint requires that pitches on strong beats be more stable, since pitch could vary freely without disrupting the meter.\n298\tThe same puzzle arises for repetition.\n299\tReducing information load is a plausible general motivation for why repetition exists in music at all, 62 but it does not explain why one particular repetition pattern dominates, nor why some positions within a repeating pattern are more tightly conserved than others.\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "fa2c8c86-2844-4ac7-abbf-ca6d31e6e24b", "uuid": "bc3fa86a-804f-4ca1-9eec-5fb58d08fe5e", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T12:11:11.322Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_lines.txt", "content": "(C) Log-odds score (log-odds of observed to expected rate) versus intervallic distance ( PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$85\\text{\\,}\\%$ ).\nGrey line and shaded region show a linear fit with 95 % 95\\text{\\,}\\% confidence interval (Pearson’s r = − 0.82 r=-0.82 , p = 0.001 p=0.001 , n = 13 n=13 ).\n(D) Substitution rate at each eighth-note position within a 6/8 measure, coloured by metrical hierarchy.\nError bars show bootstrapped 95 % 95\\text{\\,}\\% confidence intervals.\n(E) Normalised substitution rate versus metrical hierarchy, pooled across five meters (4/4, 6/8, 2/4, 9/8, 12/8), coloured by meter ( r = 0.71 r=0.71 , p = 4.8 × 10 − 7 p=4.8\\times 10^{-7} ).\n(F) Position-position covariance matrix, Σ i ​ j \\Sigma_{ij} , for all 6/8 tune pairs ( PID ≥ 50 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$50\\text{\\,}\\%$ ).\n(G) Repetition covariance for the same pairs: the component of Σ i ​ j \\Sigma_{ij} arising from position pairs linked by within-tune pitch repetition in both sequences.\nExplanations for these patterns Having shown that comparable analyses can be robustly performed on protein sequences and melodies, producing meaningful but different results, we now turn to testing exploratory hypotheses that attempt to explain these patterns.\nConserved notes are more useful for key-finding.\nThe strong correlation between pitch mutability and prevalence (Fig.\n2 B) begs an explanation.\nOne candidate is key and mode identification: prevalent notes may be those most useful for establishing a tune’s tonality, which in turn constrains the set of likely pitches and thereby facilitates recognition, learning, and memory.\nThis hypothesis predicts that the stable notes will be the most informative about tonality.\nFor an exploratory test, we develop a key-finding algorithm trained on TheSession collection (see Key Estimation), and evaluate it by estimating the key from only the first N N notes of each tune (Fig.\n3 A).\nThe algorithm achieves about 65 % 65\\text{\\,}\\% accuracy using only the first 10 10 notes.\nThis is well above chance ( 12.5 % 12.5\\text{\\,}\\% ), and it may be close to the practical limit, since tonality is not strictly established in many Irish tunes, which was historically practised without harmonic accompaniment.\nWe then apply this algorithm to the N N most- and least-conserved note positions within tune families ( PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$85\\text{\\,}\\%$ ).\nThe most-conserved notes are substantially more useful in key determination than the least-conserved notes (Fig.\n3 A), with a difference in accuracy of 34 % 34\\text{\\,}\\% at N = 10 N=10 , which persists even beyond N = 50 N=50 .\nThis shows that evolutionarily stable notes carry disproportionate information about the tonal identity of a tune.\nKey-finding is functionally useful because knowledge of key and mode constrains the set of likely pitches, making melodies easier to predict and perceive.\nWe can see this reflected in the data by looking at entropy, an information-theoretic measure of complexity 62 .\nPitch class entropy across the full dataset is 3.05 bits, falling to 2.75 bits when tunes are considered within individual keys and modes – a 10 % 10\\text{\\,}\\% reduction.\nStable notes thus appear to help achieve cognitive economy, and their stability may be maintained by selection pressure on learnability and memorability.\nSubstitution distances are constrained by melodic motion.\nThe pitch substitution matrix (Fig.\n2 D) showed clustering along the scalar diagonal, hinting that interval size is the relevant similarity metric for pitch substitution.\nOne candidate explanation is that the motor constraints governing melodic motion also govern which notes substitute, so that substitutions are limited to those that maintain the melodic style.\nUnlike amino acids, pitches have a natural, one-dimensional similarity metric, so we can measure substitution rate as a continuous function of intervallic distance and test this directly.\nIt also lets us probe whether octave equivalence, the perceptual tendency to hear pitches an octave apart as similar, 63 plays a role.\nWe first measure absolute substitution rate as a function of intervallic distance for TheSession tune parts ( PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq$85\\text{\\,}\\%$ ), since this is what was previously calculated for the Bronson and Japanese collections.\n14 We divided each rate curve by its integral to aid visual comparison (Fig.\n3 B).\nHere we can see similarities between the three collections.\nThe most notable difference is that TheSession tunes have much higher note-substitution rates at large intervallic distances (7 and 12 semitones) than found previously.\nThis perhaps reflects different constraints on melodic evolution in vocal (Bronson and Japanese) vs instrumental (TheSession) music.\nThe instrumental tunes often contain melodic passages that follow arpeggiated (3, 4, 5 or 7 semitones) rather than scalar motion (1 or 2 semitones), presumably because the motor constraints are much weaker for instruments.\nCrucially, the substitution rate closely mirrors the overall melodic interval distribution (Pearson’s r = 0.98 r=0.98 , p &lt; 10 − 8 p&lt;10^{-8} , n = 13 n=13 ): substitutions tend to span the same intervals that are prevalent in the style.\nArpeggiated passages are particularly prone to substitution, since the harmonically equivalent notes of a triad are all plausible alternatives; scalar passages in contrast typically move in a clear direction, limiting available options for variation.\nNormalising by the expected rate – i.e.\n, accounting for expectations due to scalar structure – (Fig.\n3 C) makes the dominant trend stark: substitution rate decreases log-linearly with intervallic distance, falling by approximately 20 % 20\\text{\\,}\\% per semitone.\nTwo deviations stand out – tritone substitutions (6 semitones) are rarer than expected; while octave substitutions (12 semitones) are much more common – consistent with spectral similarity and octave equivalence as alternate dimensions of pitch similarity.\nMetrical hierarchy generalises across meters.\nThe pooled relationship in Fig.\n2 F uses rhythmic strength – the empirical probability of a note onset at each metric position – as a data-driven proxy for metrical hierarchy.\nWe now highlight this relationship further using expert-annotated metrical strength – an indicator of how strongly notes at metric positions are accentuated by performers.\nWithin 6/8 tunes, substitution rates vary systematically with position, in a pattern that closely follows metrical hierarchy (Fig.\n3 D; other meters in Supplementary Fig.\n5).\nNotes on metrically strong positions are the most stable, and notes at the end of each measure the most mutable.\nWhen we pool across the five main meters and regress substitution rate against expert-annotated metrical hierarchy, the correlation remains strong (Pearson’s r = 0.71 r=0.71 , p = 4.8 × 10 − 7 p=4.8\\times 10^{-7} ; Fig.\n3 E), replicating and extending a similar finding in Savage et al.\n14 .\nWhy should metrical strength predict stability at all?\nSubstituting a pitch on a strong beat would not disrupt the meter itself, so the pattern cannot be reduced to a rhythmic constraint.\nInstead, these results are consistent with the hypothesis that metrically strong positions collectively form a stable “melodic skeleton” 30 that encodes tune identity and keeps variants mutually compatible in ensemble performance.\nLong-ranged covariance is due to repetition.\nThe short-range covariance visible in Fig.\n2 H reflects the constraint on scalar motion identified above (Fig.\n3 C): neighbouring pitches tend to move together to maintain melodic motion.\nFor the long-range periodicities, we hypothesised that they reflect repetition within the tune: motifs that recur at fixed metrical distances will naturally generate periodic correlations between their positions.\nTo test this, we compute a repetition-specific covariance matrix (see Covariance and Repetition) that isolates the component of covariance arising from within-tune pitch repetition.\nFig.\n3 F shows the full position-position covariance for 6/8 tunes (analogous to Fig.\n2 H for 4/4 tunes), and Fig.\n3 G the corresponding repetition component.\nThe repetition-only matrix reproduces the periodicities of the full matrix, confirming that long-range covariance is consistent with the cyclical repetition structure of the tune.\nThe need to preserve the structure and degree of repetition across variants therefore constrains how these melodies can evolve.\niscussion Proteins and melodies differ fundamentally because melodies have rhythm – a hierarchical feature with no molecular counterpart.\nThis difference hinders the transfer of bioinformatics methods to music, since standard alignment algorithms cannot appropriately represent the subdivision and fusion of notes.\nHowever, once we solved the alignment problem for highly-structured melodies, the rest of the standard bioinformatics toolkit transferred cleanly.\nEach of the four canonical analyses uncovers clear statistical regularities in both molecular and melodic evolution, but the patterns are categorically different between the two domains.\nThose differences are informative about the evolutionary forces that shape each: biochemical and biophysical constraints for proteins; social transmission and individual cognitive and motor biases for melodies.\nThe combination of these forces makes melodies a promising model system for understanding the interplay of these cognitive factors in cultural evolution.\nHypothesis: cognitive and motor biases shape melodic variation.\nTwo of our findings suggest independent transmission biases at the level of the individual learner.\nEvolutionary stability tracks tonal hierarchy: the tonic and dominant (‘C’ and ‘G’ in the key of C) are the most stable pitch classes, while the least stable are those absent from specific modes (Fig.\n2 B).\nThis contrasts with amino acids, where prevalence and stability reflect a mix of functional, structural, and biosynthetic factors.\nA simple hypothesis is that stable notes are those most useful for establishing key and mode, since a clear sense of tonality reduces the information burden on performers and facilitates predictive coding, learning and memory.\nOur key-finding analysis supports this: the most evolutionarily stable notes are the most informative for key estimation, consistent with predictive cognitive constraints on cultural transmission (Fig.\n3 A).\nThe two components of this hypothesis – stable notes are good for key-finding, knowledge of a key improves learning and memory – can be directly tested with cognitive experiments.\nAn alternate hypothesis is that both prevalence and stability are both products of a third component, such as a cultural attractor towards certain pitches.\nMotor constraints leave a separate signature in the substitution pattern.\nSubstitution rates mirror the melodic interval distribution of each style (Fig.\n3 B, r = 0.98 r=0.98 ), meaning that substitutions tend to span the same intervals that are common in normal melodic motion.\nThe higher rates of substitutions at large arpeggiated intervals (5 or 7 semitones) in TheSession compared to vocal collections likely reflect weaker motor constraints on large pitch jumps on instruments than for the voice – a fiddle or flute can leap more easily than a singer.\nA direct test would be to compare substitution matrices across traditions differing systematically in instrumental versus vocal performance.\nThe vocal-instrumental dichotomy can be broadened to include the fact that different instruments lead to different constraints – single-string chordophones should exhibit more similar behaviour to the voice compared to multi-string chordophones, where large intervals are facilitated by strings tuned to different pitches.\nHypothesis: a stable melodic skeleton encodes tune identity.\nPitch variation is organised along a temporal hierarchy, both at the within-measure metrical level (Fig.\n3 E), and the between-measure level where repetition is clearly structured (Fig.\n3 G).\nMetrical hierarchy itself has an obvious functional basis in dance – strong beats are marked by higher onset probability, and this rhythmic regularity is what makes the beat perceptible and the tune danceable.\nBut this explains only the rhythm, not the pitch; nothing about the metrical constraint requires that pitches on strong beats be more stable, since pitch could vary freely without disrupting the meter.\nThe same puzzle arises for repetition.\nReducing information load is a plausible general motivation for why repetition exists in music at all, 62 but it does not explain why one particular repetition pattern dominates, nor why some positions within a repeating pattern are more tightly conserved than others.", "numLines": 100, "startLine": 200, "totalLines": 1272}}}
{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1784117486186", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "chatcmpl-tool-be947f42f1b706c6", "name": "Read", "input": {"file_path": "/tmp/paper_lines.txt", "limit": 100, "offset": 300}}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "fa2c8c86-2844-4ac7-abbf-ca6d31e6e24b", "uuid": "8626eb16-6176-43d9-86d8-c2b92b59afa5"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-be947f42f1b706c6", "type": "tool_result", "content": "300\tOur results are consistent with the hypothesis that the hierarchical organisation of pitch stability reflects a heightened role of regular metrical positions – a stable melodic skeleton – in encoding tune identity.\n301\t10 ; 37 ; 26 ; 30 In our data this skeleton is directly visible as the conserved (red) positions in the conservation strip for “Man of the House” (Fig.\n302\t2 F, top), which recur at regular metrical intervals and are interleaved with the variable (blue) positions that carry most substitutions.\n303\tStrong metrical positions are not only more frequently sounded but also accentuated by performers through dynamics, microtiming, and ornamentation, making them particularly salient – more likely to be attended to, more faithfully perceived, and more reliably recalled.\n304\t64 Their regularity also allows compression: rather than memorising the skeletal positions of every tune separately, a listener can rely on a template shared across all tunes in a given meter, onto which tune-specific pitches are mapped.\n305\tA social force acts alongside this cognitive one: in ensemble playing, conformity bias is most consequential at positions where a pitch mismatch between players would be most audible – the strong metrical positions.\n306\tRepetition extends the same logic at a longer scale: in an 8-bar part, bars 1, 2, and 4 tend to be echoed in bars 5, 6, and 8, leaving bars 3 and 7 as the positions where pitch can vary most freely.\n307\tThis structure gives the melodic skeleton an internal shape that identifies the tune at the level of the part, while preserving space for the melodic variation prized in the Irish tradition.\n308\t28 Four predictions follow from this hypothesis.\n309\tFirst, the conformity mechanism predicts that positional stability should be higher in ensemble-based traditions than in predominantly solo repertoires.\n310\tSecond, iterated-learning experiments could be performed where note salience is manipulated – whether due to metrical hierarchy or even non-metric accentuation – and should show that pitch is more stable on more salient positions 64 after repeated cycles of cultural transmission.\n311\tThis should occur even when participants learn in isolation, disentangling the cognitive mechanism from the social one.\n312\tThird, hierarchical chunking of memory for these melodies should coincide with the hierarchical nature of the metrical structure 65 ; 66 .\n313\tFourth, and most directly, enculturated listeners should be able to recognise a tune from its skeletal pitches alone, and artificial variants generated by perturbing skeletal versus non-skeletal pitches should differ in how natural they are judged to sound.\n314\tTogether these tests would distinguish the proposed mechanisms and assess whether the skeleton genuinely carries tune identity.\n315\tUniversal and stylistic features of melody evolution.\n316\tWe primarily studied one tradition, but the analyses that do not require full alignment can be applied to any collection with tune family annotations.\n317\tThe mutability-prevalence relationship (correlation between evolutionary stability and tonal hierarchy) replicates in both the Bronson ( r = − 0.81 r=-0.81 , p = 0.008 p=0.008 , n = 9 n=9 ) and Japanese ( r = − 0.84 r=-0.84 , p = 0.009 p=0.009 , n = 8 n=8 ) collections, consistent with tonal hierarchies being a general feature of music.\n318\t67 The log-linear relationship between substitution rate and interval size is similarly likely to be widespread, since scalar motion dominates melodic motion across cultures.\n319\t62 By contrast, the specific covariance periodicities and mode-dependent substitution matrices are likely style-specific.\n320\tEven these are likely drawn from a discrete inventory of possible forms, in line with evidence that metrical structures 68 and pitch class sets 69 ; 70 cluster around a small number of recurring types across cultures.\n321\tCharting where traditions converge and diverge across this formal inventory – for repetition patterns as much as for modes or meters – would itself be informative about the cultural and structural constraints that shape melodic evolution.\n322\tKnowledge transfer: opportunities, pitfalls, and future directions.\n323\tBioinformatics provided not only algorithms in this study, but also a useful conceptual template.\n324\tThe hierarchical structure of melodies, with parts nested within tunes, maps naturally onto the domain/gene distinction in molecular evolution.\n325\tParts can evolve semi-independently, be rearranged within a tune, or recombine to form new ones.\n326\tThis conceptual transfer from molecular to melodic sequence analysis was as valuable as any algorithmic one.\n327\tAlong with these advantages come pitfalls, of which rhythm is the central one: pitch-only alignment is not merely suboptimal but sometimes structurally incorrect, since a gap cannot represent the subdivision or fusion of a note.\n328\tWhen a long note is divided into shorter notes, aligning some notes and assigning gaps to others fundamentally misrepresents the evolutionary relationship: subdivision of a note into multiple notes requires an alignment representation that permits one-to-many note mapping across sequences.\n329\tSavage et al.\n330\t14 record such events as insertions/deletions, which they found to outnumber substitutions – the opposite of coding DNA.\n331\tSince our grid representation maps subdivided notes onto the metrical grid rather than onto gaps, they are absorbed as one-to-many correspondences and never counted as indels.\n332\tThis is appropriate for rigid-meter dance tunes, where subdivision preserves the meter; but in free-meter or solo singing traditions, lengthening a phrase to fit a new syllable genuinely inserts material, making the same event a true indel.\n333\tThe Bronson collection contains both, and distinguishing them may lead to different results than previously found.\n334\t14 A second pitfall is fidelity of methodological transfer – knowing which elements of a canonical analysis to preserve, and which to adapt to the new domain.\n335\tThe substitution matrix illustrates both.\n336\tThe canonical Dayhoff formulation 17 normalizes observed substitutions by the rates expected under the background distribution, identifying substitution preferences rather than raw counts.\n337\tWithout normalization, two common elements dominate the matrix simply because they are common, and the standard interpretation of functional similarity between commonly-substituted elements is no longer valid (Supplementary Section 5).\n338\tA separate modification is also required: the canonical Dayhoff formulation assumes a single background distribution, which does not fit melodies obeying distinct modes, since tunes stick to a single set of notes defined by mode, limiting possible substitutions.\n339\tFor example, pooling across modes leads to high expected rates of substitutions between major and minor thirds, but in practice this almost never occurs.\n340\tWe avoided this issue by normalizing substitution matrices separately for each mode.\n341\tAvoiding potential pitfalls of this kind – recognising which analytic conventions can be preserved and which require modification – requires genuine expertise in both domains.\n342\tThe most pressing unresolved problem is achieving general-purpose melodic alignment.\n343\tThe present analysis was possible because Irish dance tunes have unusually strict structure.\n344\tFor traditions with more variable form – such as the Bronson ballads, where variants can differ in phrase length, meter, tempo, and mode – no reliable automated alignment method yet exists.\n345\tIncorporating rhythm into a dynamic programming framework is an obvious future direction, though the combinatorial explosion of possible alignments may require solutions analogous to the combinatorial extension technique developed for protein structural alignment.\n346\t71 One can learn from earlier work that considered the types of possible transformations that occur in melodies.\n347\t9 ; 10 ; 26 ; 11 ; 72 The ground-truth alignments we release here provide a benchmark for evaluating whatever approaches are developed.\n348\tThe more fundamental open question is evaluation: what does it even mean for a melodic alignment to be correct when the sequences differ in meter or phrase structure?\n349\tAnswering this will require collaboration between researchers with algorithmic and musicological expertise.\n350\tThe data are not the limiting factor: for Irish music alone, public repositories, historical recordings, and archival notation amount to hundreds of thousands of tunes, 73 ; 74 and digitisation efforts are underway for many other traditions.\n351\t75 ; 76 ; 77 ; 41 ; 78 Once algorithmic bottlenecks are resolved, the scale of available material makes this a potentially transformative moment for the computational study of musical evolution.\n352\tBridging corpus-based and experimental cultural evolution.\n353\tResearch on cultural evolution divides into two complementary traditions.\n354\tControlled experiments on memory, perception, and iterated learning isolate roles of social transmission and cognitive biases – showing, for instance, how rapidly humans acquire statistical tonal structure, 79 and disentangling the contributions of motor constraints, 80 instrumental 81 ; 82 versus vocal 83 ; 84 production, and differing modes of social transmission 85 .\n355\tBut such experiments are inherently limited: they cover only a small fraction of the stimulus space, their stimuli lack ecological validity, their participant samples are small and potentially unrepresentative, and evolution in the lab spans at most a few generations.\n356\tObservational studies of cultural corpora make the opposite tradeoff: they register the joint outcome of all biases acting simultaneously over many generations of real transmission, but lack the causal explanatory power that comes with experimental control.\n357\tFurthermore, corpus-based data-driven methods can be tackled by computational approaches that are easily scaled and adapted to other cultures.\n358\tPairing observation with modelling 86 ; 87 will let the two halves inform one another.\n359\tWe suggest that music is an unusually clean domain for studying the forces involved in cultural evolution 88 ; 89 ; 90 ; 91 .\n360\tCultural traits vary in how tightly functional pressures pin them down: language is bound to preserve meaning and grammatical structure, which sharply limits how it can change.\n361\tMelodies do not have such strong functional constraints, which we argue means that music offers a much sharper lens into the transmission and cognitive biases that shape cultural evolution.\n362\t92 onclusion The large-scale analysis of biological sequences has transformed our understanding of molecular evolution – revealing functional constraints, structural principles, and evolutionary histories that could not be inferred from individual sequences alone.\n363\tFolk melodies share multiple key properties that make this same sequence analysis approach appealing and potentially powerful: they are one-dimensional sequences drawn from a limited alphabet, transmitted with copying error, and subject to selection.\n364\tYet previous attempts to apply bioinformatics methods to melodies have been limited in how they treated rhythm and by small sample sizes.\n365\tHere we addressed these limitations systematically.\n366\tA rhythm-aware alignment method, applied to 40 , 000 40,000 Irish dance tune variants, enabled the first large-scale automated melodic alignment, and our analysis yielded four statistical signatures of melodic evolution.\n367\tThese signatures point to distinct evolutionary forces – cognitive, motor, and social – that jointly shape how melodies change, and motivate the hypothesis that a stable “melodic skeleton” encodes tune identity.\n368\tThe ground-truth alignments we release provide a benchmark for future algorithmic development toward more general melodic alignment.\n369\tThe broader significance lies in what this approach promises.\n370\tMelodies are among the best-documented examples of cultural transmission, and the methods demonstrated here can be extended to other musical traditions.\n371\tUnderstanding how cultural sequences evolve – what is conserved, what changes, and why – is a fundamental question in human cultural evolution, and one that large-scale computational analyses can now begin to answer.\n372\tethods Datasets We study four datasets comprising Irish (TheSession), 93 Dutch (Meertens), 76 British/American (Bronson) and Japanese music.\n373\t37 ; 94 ; 14 TheSession is the main dataset which we use in all analyses.\n374\tAll except the Japanese corpus include tune family annotations that can be used as ground-truth clusters of related tune variants.\n375\tWe use the Meertens dataset only for identifying similar tunes.\n376\tWe use the Bronson and Japanese tunes for note mutability and substitution analyses, and to replicate some results from a previous study.\n377\t14 TheSession – “thesession.org” is a website that hosts transcriptions of (mainly Irish) tunes which have been contributed by users over a period of about 30 years.\n378\t93 In Irish folk music melodic variation is common both within and between performances.\n379\tHence, tunes exist in many forms and the website allows users to contribute multiple variants of the same tune.\n380\tThere are currently 54 , 075 54,075 tunes grouped into 22 , 702 22,702 tune families, of which 1 , 874 1,874 have more than 5 5 variants.\n381\tWe here summarize the key metrical, structural and tonal characteristics of the data, and we refer the reader to the Supplementary Section 1 for a more comprehensive description of the dataset.\n382\tMeter: Tunes are classified by the dances associated with them, and each class is played in a specific meter.\n383\tMeter is a specification of how many beats there are in a bar and which should be accented – e.g.\n384\t, 4/4 means four quarter notes, and 6/8 means six eighth notes.\n385\tHere we primarily study five meter types: 4/4 (reel, hornpipe), 6/8 (jig), 2/4 (polka, march), 9/8 (slip jig), and 12/8 (slide).\n386\tReels and jigs are by far the most common.\n387\tStructure: These dance tunes have regular, multi-part structures.\n388\tParts are either 8 (reels, hornpipes, jigs, polkas) or 4 (slip jigs, slides) measures, and are often repeated once, yielding a simple ‘AABB’ schema for a two-part tune.\n389\tIt is the view of the first author, based on experience with the musical tradition, that parts are more stable than tunes.\n390\tA tune can vary considerably through variation in the number of parts or how they are ordered.\n391\tParts, in comparison, usually differ by a few notes while retaining a similar overall metrical and melodic structure.\n392\tVariant parts are also sometimes found in more than one distinct tune, as tunes have been created by recombination of parts from other tunes.\n393\tParts can thus be considered the more stable evolutionary unit than tunes, potentially analogous to the distinction between protein domains and full proteins.\n394\tFor this reason we divide tunes into parts and focus our analysis on alignment and comparison of parts.\n395\tTonality: Melodies are restricted to a set of pitches defined by key and mode.\n396\tThe key determines the pitch of the first note in a mode (the tonic), and the mode determines the pitches of notes based on their intervallic distance from the tonic.\n397\tThere are four 7-note modes associated with Irish dance tunes: Major, Mixolydian, Minor, and Dorian.\n398\tTunes can also contain extra notes that are not in these modes, or fewer notes such that they use 6-note or 5-note scales.\n399\tThe key and mode are annotated in the dataset, but sometimes these annotations are incorrect.\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "fa2c8c86-2844-4ac7-abbf-ca6d31e6e24b", "uuid": "2f30ab92-963d-4c6b-9df3-2722b9ad7b0a", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T12:11:28.254Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_lines.txt", "content": "Our results are consistent with the hypothesis that the hierarchical organisation of pitch stability reflects a heightened role of regular metrical positions – a stable melodic skeleton – in encoding tune identity.\n10 ; 37 ; 26 ; 30 In our data this skeleton is directly visible as the conserved (red) positions in the conservation strip for “Man of the House” (Fig.\n2 F, top), which recur at regular metrical intervals and are interleaved with the variable (blue) positions that carry most substitutions.\nStrong metrical positions are not only more frequently sounded but also accentuated by performers through dynamics, microtiming, and ornamentation, making them particularly salient – more likely to be attended to, more faithfully perceived, and more reliably recalled.\n64 Their regularity also allows compression: rather than memorising the skeletal positions of every tune separately, a listener can rely on a template shared across all tunes in a given meter, onto which tune-specific pitches are mapped.\nA social force acts alongside this cognitive one: in ensemble playing, conformity bias is most consequential at positions where a pitch mismatch between players would be most audible – the strong metrical positions.\nRepetition extends the same logic at a longer scale: in an 8-bar part, bars 1, 2, and 4 tend to be echoed in bars 5, 6, and 8, leaving bars 3 and 7 as the positions where pitch can vary most freely.\nThis structure gives the melodic skeleton an internal shape that identifies the tune at the level of the part, while preserving space for the melodic variation prized in the Irish tradition.\n28 Four predictions follow from this hypothesis.\nFirst, the conformity mechanism predicts that positional stability should be higher in ensemble-based traditions than in predominantly solo repertoires.\nSecond, iterated-learning experiments could be performed where note salience is manipulated – whether due to metrical hierarchy or even non-metric accentuation – and should show that pitch is more stable on more salient positions 64 after repeated cycles of cultural transmission.\nThis should occur even when participants learn in isolation, disentangling the cognitive mechanism from the social one.\nThird, hierarchical chunking of memory for these melodies should coincide with the hierarchical nature of the metrical structure 65 ; 66 .\nFourth, and most directly, enculturated listeners should be able to recognise a tune from its skeletal pitches alone, and artificial variants generated by perturbing skeletal versus non-skeletal pitches should differ in how natural they are judged to sound.\nTogether these tests would distinguish the proposed mechanisms and assess whether the skeleton genuinely carries tune identity.\nUniversal and stylistic features of melody evolution.\nWe primarily studied one tradition, but the analyses that do not require full alignment can be applied to any collection with tune family annotations.\nThe mutability-prevalence relationship (correlation between evolutionary stability and tonal hierarchy) replicates in both the Bronson ( r = − 0.81 r=-0.81 , p = 0.008 p=0.008 , n = 9 n=9 ) and Japanese ( r = − 0.84 r=-0.84 , p = 0.009 p=0.009 , n = 8 n=8 ) collections, consistent with tonal hierarchies being a general feature of music.\n67 The log-linear relationship between substitution rate and interval size is similarly likely to be widespread, since scalar motion dominates melodic motion across cultures.\n62 By contrast, the specific covariance periodicities and mode-dependent substitution matrices are likely style-specific.\nEven these are likely drawn from a discrete inventory of possible forms, in line with evidence that metrical structures 68 and pitch class sets 69 ; 70 cluster around a small number of recurring types across cultures.\nCharting where traditions converge and diverge across this formal inventory – for repetition patterns as much as for modes or meters – would itself be informative about the cultural and structural constraints that shape melodic evolution.\nKnowledge transfer: opportunities, pitfalls, and future directions.\nBioinformatics provided not only algorithms in this study, but also a useful conceptual template.\nThe hierarchical structure of melodies, with parts nested within tunes, maps naturally onto the domain/gene distinction in molecular evolution.\nParts can evolve semi-independently, be rearranged within a tune, or recombine to form new ones.\nThis conceptual transfer from molecular to melodic sequence analysis was as valuable as any algorithmic one.\nAlong with these advantages come pitfalls, of which rhythm is the central one: pitch-only alignment is not merely suboptimal but sometimes structurally incorrect, since a gap cannot represent the subdivision or fusion of a note.\nWhen a long note is divided into shorter notes, aligning some notes and assigning gaps to others fundamentally misrepresents the evolutionary relationship: subdivision of a note into multiple notes requires an alignment representation that permits one-to-many note mapping across sequences.\nSavage et al.\n14 record such events as insertions/deletions, which they found to outnumber substitutions – the opposite of coding DNA.\nSince our grid representation maps subdivided notes onto the metrical grid rather than onto gaps, they are absorbed as one-to-many correspondences and never counted as indels.\nThis is appropriate for rigid-meter dance tunes, where subdivision preserves the meter; but in free-meter or solo singing traditions, lengthening a phrase to fit a new syllable genuinely inserts material, making the same event a true indel.\nThe Bronson collection contains both, and distinguishing them may lead to different results than previously found.\n14 A second pitfall is fidelity of methodological transfer – knowing which elements of a canonical analysis to preserve, and which to adapt to the new domain.\nThe substitution matrix illustrates both.\nThe canonical Dayhoff formulation 17 normalizes observed substitutions by the rates expected under the background distribution, identifying substitution preferences rather than raw counts.\nWithout normalization, two common elements dominate the matrix simply because they are common, and the standard interpretation of functional similarity between commonly-substituted elements is no longer valid (Supplementary Section 5).\nA separate modification is also required: the canonical Dayhoff formulation assumes a single background distribution, which does not fit melodies obeying distinct modes, since tunes stick to a single set of notes defined by mode, limiting possible substitutions.\nFor example, pooling across modes leads to high expected rates of substitutions between major and minor thirds, but in practice this almost never occurs.\nWe avoided this issue by normalizing substitution matrices separately for each mode.\nAvoiding potential pitfalls of this kind – recognising which analytic conventions can be preserved and which require modification – requires genuine expertise in both domains.\nThe most pressing unresolved problem is achieving general-purpose melodic alignment.\nThe present analysis was possible because Irish dance tunes have unusually strict structure.\nFor traditions with more variable form – such as the Bronson ballads, where variants can differ in phrase length, meter, tempo, and mode – no reliable automated alignment method yet exists.\nIncorporating rhythm into a dynamic programming framework is an obvious future direction, though the combinatorial explosion of possible alignments may require solutions analogous to the combinatorial extension technique developed for protein structural alignment.\n71 One can learn from earlier work that considered the types of possible transformations that occur in melodies.\n9 ; 10 ; 26 ; 11 ; 72 The ground-truth alignments we release here provide a benchmark for evaluating whatever approaches are developed.\nThe more fundamental open question is evaluation: what does it even mean for a melodic alignment to be correct when the sequences differ in meter or phrase structure?\nAnswering this will require collaboration between researchers with algorithmic and musicological expertise.\nThe data are not the limiting factor: for Irish music alone, public repositories, historical recordings, and archival notation amount to hundreds of thousands of tunes, 73 ; 74 and digitisation efforts are underway for many other traditions.\n75 ; 76 ; 77 ; 41 ; 78 Once algorithmic bottlenecks are resolved, the scale of available material makes this a potentially transformative moment for the computational study of musical evolution.\nBridging corpus-based and experimental cultural evolution.\nResearch on cultural evolution divides into two complementary traditions.\nControlled experiments on memory, perception, and iterated learning isolate roles of social transmission and cognitive biases – showing, for instance, how rapidly humans acquire statistical tonal structure, 79 and disentangling the contributions of motor constraints, 80 instrumental 81 ; 82 versus vocal 83 ; 84 production, and differing modes of social transmission 85 .\nBut such experiments are inherently limited: they cover only a small fraction of the stimulus space, their stimuli lack ecological validity, their participant samples are small and potentially unrepresentative, and evolution in the lab spans at most a few generations.\nObservational studies of cultural corpora make the opposite tradeoff: they register the joint outcome of all biases acting simultaneously over many generations of real transmission, but lack the causal explanatory power that comes with experimental control.\nFurthermore, corpus-based data-driven methods can be tackled by computational approaches that are easily scaled and adapted to other cultures.\nPairing observation with modelling 86 ; 87 will let the two halves inform one another.\nWe suggest that music is an unusually clean domain for studying the forces involved in cultural evolution 88 ; 89 ; 90 ; 91 .\nCultural traits vary in how tightly functional pressures pin them down: language is bound to preserve meaning and grammatical structure, which sharply limits how it can change.\nMelodies do not have such strong functional constraints, which we argue means that music offers a much sharper lens into the transmission and cognitive biases that shape cultural evolution.\n92 onclusion The large-scale analysis of biological sequences has transformed our understanding of molecular evolution – revealing functional constraints, structural principles, and evolutionary histories that could not be inferred from individual sequences alone.\nFolk melodies share multiple key properties that make this same sequence analysis approach appealing and potentially powerful: they are one-dimensional sequences drawn from a limited alphabet, transmitted with copying error, and subject to selection.\nYet previous attempts to apply bioinformatics methods to melodies have been limited in how they treated rhythm and by small sample sizes.\nHere we addressed these limitations systematically.\nA rhythm-aware alignment method, applied to 40 , 000 40,000 Irish dance tune variants, enabled the first large-scale automated melodic alignment, and our analysis yielded four statistical signatures of melodic evolution.\nThese signatures point to distinct evolutionary forces – cognitive, motor, and social – that jointly shape how melodies change, and motivate the hypothesis that a stable “melodic skeleton” encodes tune identity.\nThe ground-truth alignments we release provide a benchmark for future algorithmic development toward more general melodic alignment.\nThe broader significance lies in what this approach promises.\nMelodies are among the best-documented examples of cultural transmission, and the methods demonstrated here can be extended to other musical traditions.\nUnderstanding how cultural sequences evolve – what is conserved, what changes, and why – is a fundamental question in human cultural evolution, and one that large-scale computational analyses can now begin to answer.\nethods Datasets We study four datasets comprising Irish (TheSession), 93 Dutch (Meertens), 76 British/American (Bronson) and Japanese music.\n37 ; 94 ; 14 TheSession is the main dataset which we use in all analyses.\nAll except the Japanese corpus include tune family annotations that can be used as ground-truth clusters of related tune variants.\nWe use the Meertens dataset only for identifying similar tunes.\nWe use the Bronson and Japanese tunes for note mutability and substitution analyses, and to replicate some results from a previous study.\n14 TheSession – “thesession.org” is a website that hosts transcriptions of (mainly Irish) tunes which have been contributed by users over a period of about 30 years.\n93 In Irish folk music melodic variation is common both within and between performances.\nHence, tunes exist in many forms and the website allows users to contribute multiple variants of the same tune.\nThere are currently 54 , 075 54,075 tunes grouped into 22 , 702 22,702 tune families, of which 1 , 874 1,874 have more than 5 5 variants.\nWe here summarize the key metrical, structural and tonal characteristics of the data, and we refer the reader to the Supplementary Section 1 for a more comprehensive description of the dataset.\nMeter: Tunes are classified by the dances associated with them, and each class is played in a specific meter.\nMeter is a specification of how many beats there are in a bar and which should be accented – e.g.\n, 4/4 means four quarter notes, and 6/8 means six eighth notes.\nHere we primarily study five meter types: 4/4 (reel, hornpipe), 6/8 (jig), 2/4 (polka, march), 9/8 (slip jig), and 12/8 (slide).\nReels and jigs are by far the most common.\nStructure: These dance tunes have regular, multi-part structures.\nParts are either 8 (reels, hornpipes, jigs, polkas) or 4 (slip jigs, slides) measures, and are often repeated once, yielding a simple ‘AABB’ schema for a two-part tune.\nIt is the view of the first author, based on experience with the musical tradition, that parts are more stable than tunes.\nA tune can vary considerably through variation in the number of parts or how they are ordered.\nParts, in comparison, usually differ by a few notes while retaining a similar overall metrical and melodic structure.\nVariant parts are also sometimes found in more than one distinct tune, as tunes have been created by recombination of parts from other tunes.\nParts can thus be considered the more stable evolutionary unit than tunes, potentially analogous to the distinction between protein domains and full proteins.\nFor this reason we divide tunes into parts and focus our analysis on alignment and comparison of parts.\nTonality: Melodies are restricted to a set of pitches defined by key and mode.\nThe key determines the pitch of the first note in a mode (the tonic), and the mode determines the pitches of notes based on their intervallic distance from the tonic.\nThere are four 7-note modes associated with Irish dance tunes: Major, Mixolydian, Minor, and Dorian.\nTunes can also contain extra notes that are not in these modes, or fewer notes such that they use 6-note or 5-note scales.\nThe key and mode are annotated in the dataset, but sometimes these annotations are incorrect.", "numLines": 100, "startLine": 300, "totalLines": 1272}}}
