{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-9c042e1101751989", "type": "tool_result", "content": "400\tWe use an algorithm to detect and re-annotate tunes with the correct modes, in cases where we can unambiguously determine a mistake and correct it (Section Mode Estimation ).\n401\tMeertens – The Meertens Tune Collection consists of 18 , 618 18,618 digitally encoded pieces.\n402\tThese include both instrumental and vocal melodies.\n403\tThe data is available in multiple formats, and we used the Kern format.\n404\t95 Tunes are classed into tune families, 83 of which have more than 2 labelled variants.\n405\tThis data is only analysed when testing if sequence alignment tools can be used for tune family identification.\n406\tBronson and Japanese – These are two collections of melodies that were digitized earlier.\n407\t14 One is the Bronson collection of ballads from Britain and North America, 37 and the other is from an anthology of Japanese folk tunes.\n408\t94 Unfortunately the melodies were digitized in a custom format that does not include any rhythm information, and pitch is represented using pitch class, which confines pitch information to a single octave.\n409\tThe authors did manually incorporate some of this information for their analyses, but it is not available in the data that was released.\n410\tA subset of 242 242 highly-related ( PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq 85\\% ) pairs of tunes were manually aligned by Savage et al.\n411\t14 .\n412\tWe use these in three ways.\n413\tFirst we use them as ground truth alignments to demonstrate the fundamental limitations of alignment algorithms that do not use rhythm information.\n414\tSecond, we recreate the note substitution matrix presented by Savage et al.\n415\t14 ; the authors only calculated raw substitution counts, whereas we instead calculate substitution preferences through the canonical Dayhoff normalization procedure.\n416\tThird, we calculate note mutability and its correlation with note prevalence (the authors provided a similar analysis in an earlier preprint version).\n417\tWe show absolute substitution rate as a function of substitution distance for both the Bronson and the Japanese collections, as a comparison with TheSession.\n418\tThese values were taken directly from the figures in 14 .\n419\tWe additionally perform some analyses that are possible using the available manually-corrected alignments, and we do not attempt to analyse alignments of these melodies that were generated algorithmically.\n420\tData Processing Pre-processing and exclusion criteria.\n421\tTunes are systematically excluded on the basis of complexity, regularity, and whether they are successfully parsed by two parsers (pyabc, music21; Section Parsers ).\n422\tWe process and exclude tunes sequentially as follows (and we report the numbers of tunes excluded at each stage): (i) Remove unnecessary elements (e.g., fermata, slur lines) (0 excluded).\n423\t(ii) Parse tune with pyabc ( 1 , 972 1,972 did not parse).\n424\t(iii) Exclude all ( 4 , 642 4,642 ) tunes that have grace notes, multiple simultaneous notes , or multiple voices (staves).\n425\tGrace notes are difficult to deal with since they have an indeterminate duration, and music21 has problems parsing grace notes in ABC format.\n426\tSimultaneous notes and multiple voices render the melody ambiguous.\n427\t(iv) Optionally exclude ( 6 , 001 6,001 ) tunes with repeat lines that do not have a matching start and end pair, in case these are used by music21 to unravel the repeats as they are actually performed.\n428\t(v) Parse the tune body using music21, unravel repeat lines, and transpose the tune to a uniform key of C ( 590 590 did not parse correctly).\n429\tThis left 41 , 050 41,050 tunes for the main analyses.\n430\tFor the first analysis in this paper where we simply identify similar tunes, we run steps up to and including (iii), which left 47 , 641 47,641 tunes.\n431\tParsers.\n432\tThe datasets have melodies stored in ABC 96 and Kern 95 formats.\n433\tWe use two python packages to parse the data, music21 97 and pyabc.\n434\t98 Music21 is able to read many symbolic notation formats, however it is less-well developed for ABC than for other file types.\n435\tFor example, music21 incorrectly parses pauses (fermata) by assuming they are notes with pitch C.\n436\tPyabc was developed specifically for parsing ABC so one might expect it to have fewer errors, however it is still under development (listed as pre-alpha on GitHub).\n437\tWe implemented several fixes and feature additions to pyabc, which have been integrated in an updated version of the software.\n438\tTo ensure quality control, we parse tunes using both parsers and check that they agree.\n439\tWe mainly use music21 because it has additional functionality over pyabc – one can “expand repeat lines” so that the melodic sequence is parsed as it should be played.\n440\tMelodic Sequence Representations.\n441\tWe represent melodies in two complementary forms: (i) a sequence of MIDI pitches paired with note durations, and (ii) a grid-quantised pitch vector – akin to piano rolls on digital audio workstations.\n442\tAfter parsing an ABC string, a melody of N N notes is represented as two sequences of equal length: a pitch sequence 𝐩 = ( p 1 , … , p N ) \\mathbf{p}=(p_{1},\\ldots,p_{N}) of MIDI integer values, and a duration sequence 𝐝 = ( d 1 , … , d N ) \\mathbf{d}=(d_{1},\\ldots,d_{N}) where each d i d_{i} is expressed in units of quarter notes.\n443\tTransposition to a common key is performed by subtracting the tonic pitch class τ \\tau (in semitones) from each element: 𝐩 τ = 𝐩 − τ .\n444\t\\mathbf{p}^{\\tau}=\\mathbf{p}-\\tau~.\n445\tFor example, when transposing from the key of ‘A’ to the key of ‘C’, τ = 9 \\tau=9 semitones.\n446\tMIDI and transposed MIDI sequences can be converted to pitch class sequences: 𝐜 = 𝐩 mod 12 ; \\mathbf{c}=\\mathbf{p}\\mod 12~; 𝐜 τ = 𝐩 τ mod 12 .\n447\t\\mathbf{c}^{\\tau}=\\mathbf{p}^{\\tau}\\mod 12~.\n448\tTo facilitate alignment, we convert a pair ( 𝐩 , 𝐝 ) (\\mathbf{p},\\mathbf{d}) into a pitch vector 𝐱 \\mathbf{x} of length L L by quantizing onto a uniform time grid.\n449\tThe grid spacing G G is the smallest common denominator of all duration values in 𝐝 \\mathbf{d} (or, when aligning two melodies, of the combined set of duration values of both tunes).\n450\tEach note is expanded to n i = d i / G n_{i}=d_{i}/G consecutive grid cells carrying its pitch.\n451\tThe total length of the vector is L = ∑ i = 1 N n i L=\\sum_{i=1}^{N}n_{i} .\n452\tThis construction can be applied to any of the four pitch sequence representations ( 𝐩 \\mathbf{p} , 𝐩 τ \\mathbf{p}^{\\tau} , 𝐜 \\mathbf{c} , 𝐜 τ \\mathbf{c}^{\\tau} ), yielding pitch vectors 𝐱 \\mathbf{x} , 𝐱 τ \\mathbf{x}^{\\tau} , 𝐱 c \\mathbf{x}^{c} , or 𝐱 c , τ \\mathbf{x}^{c,\\tau} respectively.\n453\tDividing Tunes into Parts.\n454\tWe assume that parts in TheSession tunes are either 8 or 16 measures long; see the Supplementary Section 1 for a detailed justification, and known exceptions.\n455\tTunes in 3/4 meter (annotated as ‘waltz’, but actually a mix of dance and vocal songs) are excluded since they do not have the same rigid structure that makes this assumption valid.\n456\tWe first identify and remove any pickup (anacrusis) measures – incomplete measures at the start of a tune – by counting the total duration of notes in the first measure and comparing it to the expected duration D m D_{m} for the given meter m m .\n457\tFor example, D 4 / 4 = 4 D_{4/4}=4 quarter notes.\n458\tAny tune containing a measure whose total note duration differs from D m D_{m} is excluded.\n459\tWe then count the number of measures, N measure N_{\\textrm{measure}} , and exclude any tunes if N measure mod 8 ≠ 0 N_{\\textrm{measure}}\\mod 8\\neq 0 , removing any tunes that do not fit these assumptions.\n460\tThe tune is then divided into consecutive parts of 8 measures each.\n461\tSince 8-measure parts are sometimes repeated, we identify such cases and merge neighbouring parts into a single 16-measure part if they are highly similar.\n462\tTo identify similar parts, we convert each part into pitch vectors of equal length L L , respectively 𝐱 \\mathbf{x} and 𝐱 ′ \\mathbf{x}^{\\prime} (constructed as described in Melodic Sequence Representations).\n463\tIf at least 80 % 80\\text{\\,}\\% of grid positions have the same pitch value in both parts ( PID ≥ \\textrm{PID}\\geq 80 % 80\\text{\\,}\\% ) the two parts are merged into a single 16-measure part.\n464\tWe validated this algorithm using a ground-truth set of manually-annotated parts produced by the first author, who is expert in the Irish musical tradition.\n465\tThe set consists of 6 tunes (126 variants) with annotated parts.\n466\tThe similarity threshold was allowed to vary to determine the optimal value.\n467\tA threshold of 80 % 80\\text{\\,}\\% led to 98 % 98\\text{\\,}\\% accuracy in identifying the correct number of parts.\n468\tSequence Alignment Pitch-based Sequence Comparison.\n469\tWe use the bioinformatics software MMseqs2 to compare melodies to find similar tunes.\n470\t58 This algorithm uses multiple pre-screening approaches to speed up comparisons, such that it only takes a few minutes to compare billions of tune pairs on a laptop.\n471\tFor tune pairs that pass screening, percent sequence identity ( PID ) is calculated using the Smith-Waterman (local) alignment algorithm.\n472\t99 This algorithm requires sequences to be converted to a 21-letter alphabet corresponding to the 20 amino acids and 1 wildcard.\n473\tTo ensure that our pitch sequences have fewer than 21 unique values we convert from MIDI to pitch class, 𝐜 τ \\mathbf{c}^{\\tau} .\n474\tWe transpose to a common key (C).\n475\tWe then map pitch classes onto the first 12 letters from the amino acid alphabet.\n476\tFor downstream analyses we can map these back to the original MIDI values.\n477\tWe write letter sequences to fasta files using Biopython.\n478\t100 Since MMseqs2 was optimized for biological sequences, we optimized the score parameters (match, mismatch, gap open, gap extend) so that PID best predicts the grouping of tunes into tune families: match = 6, mismatch = -4, gap open = -4, gap extend = -3 (see Supplementary Section 3).\n479\tMMseqs2 is useful for finding similar sequences, but it was not designed for producing alignments for further analysis.\n480\tFor one specific analysis we require an alignment algorithm that can produce all top-scoring alignments in case there are more than one.\n481\tFor this we use Biopython’s Align module.\n482\tRhythm-Aware Part Alignment.\n483\tDue to regularities in the structure of TheSession tunes, it is quite easy to align parts once similar parts have been identified.\n484\tFrom a total of 41 , 050 41,050 tunes we extracted 51 , 906 51,906 parts.\n485\tAn all-vs-all comparison ( ∼ \\sim 2 2 billion pairs) using MMseqs2 (see Pitch-based Sequence Alignment) identified ∼ \\sim 4 4 million pairs of parts with similarity above a standard threshold (e-value 0.001 0.001 ).\n486\tWe control for sequence redundancy by identifying clusters of identical parts and removing all but one representative part.\n487\tWe exclude pairs of parts that differ in meter or number of measures.\n488\tThis leaves pairs of parts that can be converted to equal-length pitch vectors, 𝐱 \\mathbf{x} and 𝐱 ′ \\mathbf{x}^{\\prime} , which can be compared elementwise to calculate PID .\n489\tWe do this for the remaining pairs at this stage, and exclude any pairs with PID ≤ 50 % \\textrm{PID}\\leq$50\\text{\\,}\\%$ .\n490\tThis leaves us with 51 , 680 51,680 pairs of parts for further analysis.\n491\tPercent Identity (PID).\n492\tPercent identity ( PID ) is the fraction of positions in an alignment at which two sequences share the same pitch value.\n493\t101 The denominator varies depending on the alignment method employed.\n494\tWhen using the Needleman-Wunsch (global) algorithm, 16 PID is the number of matches divided by the length of the alignment.\n495\tWhen using the Smith-Waterman (local) alignment algorithm, 99 PID is calculated in the same way as for a global alignment, but only over the aligned part of a sequence.\n496\ti.e.\n497\t, local alignments can in principle align the full sequences, but in practice the ends of sequences are not included in the alignment if they are not sufficiently similar.\n498\tWhen aligning pitch vectors, notes with long durations occupy multiple positions in the vector.\n499\tPID is again the percentage of matches, but in this case matches are effectively weighted by the total duration of the matching notes.\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "fa2c8c86-2844-4ac7-abbf-ca6d31e6e24b", "uuid": "c8c92480-8391-4678-a22b-f64119c35336", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T12:11:45.628Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/paper_lines.txt", "content": "We use an algorithm to detect and re-annotate tunes with the correct modes, in cases where we can unambiguously determine a mistake and correct it (Section Mode Estimation ).\nMeertens – The Meertens Tune Collection consists of 18 , 618 18,618 digitally encoded pieces.\nThese include both instrumental and vocal melodies.\nThe data is available in multiple formats, and we used the Kern format.\n95 Tunes are classed into tune families, 83 of which have more than 2 labelled variants.\nThis data is only analysed when testing if sequence alignment tools can be used for tune family identification.\nBronson and Japanese – These are two collections of melodies that were digitized earlier.\n14 One is the Bronson collection of ballads from Britain and North America, 37 and the other is from an anthology of Japanese folk tunes.\n94 Unfortunately the melodies were digitized in a custom format that does not include any rhythm information, and pitch is represented using pitch class, which confines pitch information to a single octave.\nThe authors did manually incorporate some of this information for their analyses, but it is not available in the data that was released.\nA subset of 242 242 highly-related ( PID ≥ 85 % \\textrm{PID}\\geq 85\\% ) pairs of tunes were manually aligned by Savage et al.\n14 .\nWe use these in three ways.\nFirst we use them as ground truth alignments to demonstrate the fundamental limitations of alignment algorithms that do not use rhythm information.\nSecond, we recreate the note substitution matrix presented by Savage et al.\n14 ; the authors only calculated raw substitution counts, whereas we instead calculate substitution preferences through the canonical Dayhoff normalization procedure.\nThird, we calculate note mutability and its correlation with note prevalence (the authors provided a similar analysis in an earlier preprint version).\nWe show absolute substitution rate as a function of substitution distance for both the Bronson and the Japanese collections, as a comparison with TheSession.\nThese values were taken directly from the figures in 14 .\nWe additionally perform some analyses that are possible using the available manually-corrected alignments, and we do not attempt to analyse alignments of these melodies that were generated algorithmically.\nData Processing Pre-processing and exclusion criteria.\nTunes are systematically excluded on the basis of complexity, regularity, and whether they are successfully parsed by two parsers (pyabc, music21; Section Parsers ).\nWe process and exclude tunes sequentially as follows (and we report the numbers of tunes excluded at each stage): (i) Remove unnecessary elements (e.g., fermata, slur lines) (0 excluded).\n(ii) Parse tune with pyabc ( 1 , 972 1,972 did not parse).\n(iii) Exclude all ( 4 , 642 4,642 ) tunes that have grace notes, multiple simultaneous notes , or multiple voices (staves).\nGrace notes are difficult to deal with since they have an indeterminate duration, and music21 has problems parsing grace notes in ABC format.\nSimultaneous notes and multiple voices render the melody ambiguous.\n(iv) Optionally exclude ( 6 , 001 6,001 ) tunes with repeat lines that do not have a matching start and end pair, in case these are used by music21 to unravel the repeats as they are actually performed.\n(v) Parse the tune body using music21, unravel repeat lines, and transpose the tune to a uniform key of C ( 590 590 did not parse correctly).\nThis left 41 , 050 41,050 tunes for the main analyses.\nFor the first analysis in this paper where we simply identify similar tunes, we run steps up to and including (iii), which left 47 , 641 47,641 tunes.\nParsers.\nThe datasets have melodies stored in ABC 96 and Kern 95 formats.\nWe use two python packages to parse the data, music21 97 and pyabc.\n98 Music21 is able to read many symbolic notation formats, however it is less-well developed for ABC than for other file types.\nFor example, music21 incorrectly parses pauses (fermata) by assuming they are notes with pitch C.\nPyabc was developed specifically for parsing ABC so one might expect it to have fewer errors, however it is still under development (listed as pre-alpha on GitHub).\nWe implemented several fixes and feature additions to pyabc, which have been integrated in an updated version of the software.\nTo ensure quality control, we parse tunes using both parsers and check that they agree.\nWe mainly use music21 because it has additional functionality over pyabc – one can “expand repeat lines” so that the melodic sequence is parsed as it should be played.\nMelodic Sequence Representations.\nWe represent melodies in two complementary forms: (i) a sequence of MIDI pitches paired with note durations, and (ii) a grid-quantised pitch vector – akin to piano rolls on digital audio workstations.\nAfter parsing an ABC string, a melody of N N notes is represented as two sequences of equal length: a pitch sequence 𝐩 = ( p 1 , … , p N ) \\mathbf{p}=(p_{1},\\ldots,p_{N}) of MIDI integer values, and a duration sequence 𝐝 = ( d 1 , … , d N ) \\mathbf{d}=(d_{1},\\ldots,d_{N}) where each d i d_{i} is expressed in units of quarter notes.\nTransposition to a common key is performed by subtracting the tonic pitch class τ \\tau (in semitones) from each element: 𝐩 τ = 𝐩 − τ .\n\\mathbf{p}^{\\tau}=\\mathbf{p}-\\tau~.\nFor example, when transposing from the key of ‘A’ to the key of ‘C’, τ = 9 \\tau=9 semitones.\nMIDI and transposed MIDI sequences can be converted to pitch class sequences: 𝐜 = 𝐩 mod 12 ; \\mathbf{c}=\\mathbf{p}\\mod 12~; 𝐜 τ = 𝐩 τ mod 12 .\n\\mathbf{c}^{\\tau}=\\mathbf{p}^{\\tau}\\mod 12~.\nTo facilitate alignment, we convert a pair ( 𝐩 , 𝐝 ) (\\mathbf{p},\\mathbf{d}) into a pitch vector 𝐱 \\mathbf{x} of length L L by quantizing onto a uniform time grid.\nThe grid spacing G G is the smallest common denominator of all duration values in 𝐝 \\mathbf{d} (or, when aligning two melodies, of the combined set of duration values of both tunes).\nEach note is expanded to n i = d i / G n_{i}=d_{i}/G consecutive grid cells carrying its pitch.\nThe total length of the vector is L = ∑ i = 1 N n i L=\\sum_{i=1}^{N}n_{i} .\nThis construction can be applied to any of the four pitch sequence representations ( 𝐩 \\mathbf{p} , 𝐩 τ \\mathbf{p}^{\\tau} , 𝐜 \\mathbf{c} , 𝐜 τ \\mathbf{c}^{\\tau} ), yielding pitch vectors 𝐱 \\mathbf{x} , 𝐱 τ \\mathbf{x}^{\\tau} , 𝐱 c \\mathbf{x}^{c} , or 𝐱 c , τ \\mathbf{x}^{c,\\tau} respectively.\nDividing Tunes into Parts.\nWe assume that parts in TheSession tunes are either 8 or 16 measures long; see the Supplementary Section 1 for a detailed justification, and known exceptions.\nTunes in 3/4 meter (annotated as ‘waltz’, but actually a mix of dance and vocal songs) are excluded since they do not have the same rigid structure that makes this assumption valid.\nWe first identify and remove any pickup (anacrusis) measures – incomplete measures at the start of a tune – by counting the total duration of notes in the first measure and comparing it to the expected duration D m D_{m} for the given meter m m .\nFor example, D 4 / 4 = 4 D_{4/4}=4 quarter notes.\nAny tune containing a measure whose total note duration differs from D m D_{m} is excluded.\nWe then count the number of measures, N measure N_{\\textrm{measure}} , and exclude any tunes if N measure mod 8 ≠ 0 N_{\\textrm{measure}}\\mod 8\\neq 0 , removing any tunes that do not fit these assumptions.\nThe tune is then divided into consecutive parts of 8 measures each.\nSince 8-measure parts are sometimes repeated, we identify such cases and merge neighbouring parts into a single 16-measure part if they are highly similar.\nTo identify similar parts, we convert each part into pitch vectors of equal length L L , respectively 𝐱 \\mathbf{x} and 𝐱 ′ \\mathbf{x}^{\\prime} (constructed as described in Melodic Sequence Representations).\nIf at least 80 % 80\\text{\\,}\\% of grid positions have the same pitch value in both parts ( PID ≥ \\textrm{PID}\\geq 80 % 80\\text{\\,}\\% ) the two parts are merged into a single 16-measure part.\nWe validated this algorithm using a ground-truth set of manually-annotated parts produced by the first author, who is expert in the Irish musical tradition.\nThe set consists of 6 tunes (126 variants) with annotated parts.\nThe similarity threshold was allowed to vary to determine the optimal value.\nA threshold of 80 % 80\\text{\\,}\\% led to 98 % 98\\text{\\,}\\% accuracy in identifying the correct number of parts.\nSequence Alignment Pitch-based Sequence Comparison.\nWe use the bioinformatics software MMseqs2 to compare melodies to find similar tunes.\n58 This algorithm uses multiple pre-screening approaches to speed up comparisons, such that it only takes a few minutes to compare billions of tune pairs on a laptop.\nFor tune pairs that pass screening, percent sequence identity ( PID ) is calculated using the Smith-Waterman (local) alignment algorithm.\n99 This algorithm requires sequences to be converted to a 21-letter alphabet corresponding to the 20 amino acids and 1 wildcard.\nTo ensure that our pitch sequences have fewer than 21 unique values we convert from MIDI to pitch class, 𝐜 τ \\mathbf{c}^{\\tau} .\nWe transpose to a common key (C).\nWe then map pitch classes onto the first 12 letters from the amino acid alphabet.\nFor downstream analyses we can map these back to the original MIDI values.\nWe write letter sequences to fasta files using Biopython.\n100 Since MMseqs2 was optimized for biological sequences, we optimized the score parameters (match, mismatch, gap open, gap extend) so that PID best predicts the grouping of tunes into tune families: match = 6, mismatch = -4, gap open = -4, gap extend = -3 (see Supplementary Section 3).\nMMseqs2 is useful for finding similar sequences, but it was not designed for producing alignments for further analysis.\nFor one specific analysis we require an alignment algorithm that can produce all top-scoring alignments in case there are more than one.\nFor this we use Biopython’s Align module.\nRhythm-Aware Part Alignment.\nDue to regularities in the structure of TheSession tunes, it is quite easy to align parts once similar parts have been identified.\nFrom a total of 41 , 050 41,050 tunes we extracted 51 , 906 51,906 parts.\nAn all-vs-all comparison ( ∼ \\sim 2 2 billion pairs) using MMseqs2 (see Pitch-based Sequence Alignment) identified ∼ \\sim 4 4 million pairs of parts with similarity above a standard threshold (e-value 0.001 0.001 ).\nWe control for sequence redundancy by identifying clusters of identical parts and removing all but one representative part.\nWe exclude pairs of parts that differ in meter or number of measures.\nThis leaves pairs of parts that can be converted to equal-length pitch vectors, 𝐱 \\mathbf{x} and 𝐱 ′ \\mathbf{x}^{\\prime} , which can be compared elementwise to calculate PID .\nWe do this for the remaining pairs at this stage, and exclude any pairs with PID ≤ 50 % \\textrm{PID}\\leq$50\\text{\\,}\\%$ .\nThis leaves us with 51 , 680 51,680 pairs of parts for further analysis.\nPercent Identity (PID).\nPercent identity ( PID ) is the fraction of positions in an alignment at which two sequences share the same pitch value.\n101 The denominator varies depending on the alignment method employed.\nWhen using the Needleman-Wunsch (global) algorithm, 16 PID is the number of matches divided by the length of the alignment.\nWhen using the Smith-Waterman (local) alignment algorithm, 99 PID is calculated in the same way as for a global alignment, but only over the aligned part of a sequence.\ni.e.\n, local alignments can in principle align the full sequences, but in practice the ends of sequences are not included in the alignment if they are not sufficiently similar.\nWhen aligning pitch vectors, notes with long durations occupy multiple positions in the vector.\nPID is again the percentage of matches, but in this case matches are effectively weighted by the total duration of the matching notes.", "numLines": 100, "startLine": 400, "totalLines": 1272}}}
