{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-903e740b36394e84", "type": "tool_result", "content": "500\tSample Weighting.\n501\tSome tunes have many more variants than others, producing a long-tailed distribution over tune IDs.\n502\tThis problem is exacerbated when comparing pairs, since the joint distribution over pairs has an even heavier tail.\n503\tTo avoid results being dominated by the most common tunes, we apply inverse-frequency sample weights, w i = q i − 1 w_{i}=q_{i}^{-1} , where w i w_{i} is the weight of tune i i , and q i q_{i} is the fraction of all instances of tune i i in the full set of pairs.\n504\tThis approach has the downside of increasing variance, since it increases the relative weight of rare IDs.\n505\t102 We can reduce this effect by modifying the weighting, w i = q i − α w_{i}=q^{-\\alpha}_{i} , where 0 ≤ α ≤ 1 0\\leq\\alpha\\leq 1 .\n506\tWhen α = 0 \\alpha=0 samples are weighted (and biased) by the number of variants per tune.\n507\tWhen α = 1 \\alpha=1 we recover the inverse-frequency weighting which increases variance due to over-weighting rare tunes.\n508\tSince we are analysing pairs of parts that can come from different tunes, we weight by the geometric mean of the weights of the two parts.\n509\tWe use a value of α = 0.5 \\alpha=0.5 as a compromise between bias and variance, and run sensitivity analyses to test robustness of results to weighting.\n510\tBioinformatic Analyses on Melodies Pitch Mutability.\n511\tFor a set of aligned sequence pairs, we first convert them to transposed pitch class vectors 𝐱 c , τ \\mathbf{x}_{c,\\tau} .\n512\tWe count pitch class occurrence – how many grid positions each pitch class occupies overall – and co-occurrence of all pitch-class pairs – how many grid positions each pair of pitch classes co-occur across alignments.\n513\tSubstitutions are co-occurrences of one pitch class with another.\n514\tMutability of pitch class c c is the fraction of its occurrences that involve a substitution – the number of substitutions divided by occurrences.\n515\tFor example, if D occurs 100 times and is substituted 20 times, μ ​ ( D ) = 0.2 \\mu(D)=0.2 .\n516\tSubstitution Matrices.\n517\tThe absolute substitution rate between two pitch classes is simply their co-occurrence count at substituted positions in ( 𝐱 c , τ , 𝐱 c , τ ′ ) (\\mathbf{x}_{c,\\tau},\\mathbf{x}_{c,\\tau}^{\\prime}) pairs; this is what was calculated by 14 .\n518\tHowever, this is dominated by the most common pitch classes.\n519\tFollowing the original bioinformatics methodology from Dayhoff et al.\n520\t17 , we compute a normalized score: S ​ ( c , c ′ ) = log ⁡ p ^ ​ ( c , c ′ ) p ^ ​ ( c ) ⋅ p ^ ​ ( c ′ ) S(c,c^{\\prime})=\\log\\frac{\\hat{p}(c,c^{\\prime})}{\\hat{p}(c)\\cdot\\hat{p}(c^{\\prime})} where p ^ ​ ( c , c ′ ) \\hat{p}(c,c^{\\prime}) is the observed probability of c c and c ′ c^{\\prime} co-occurring at a position, and p ^ ​ ( c ) ⋅ p ^ ​ ( c ′ ) \\hat{p}(c)\\cdot\\hat{p}(c^{\\prime}) is the probability expected if the two pitch classes occurred independently.\n521\tFor example, if p ^ ​ ( C ) = 0.2 \\hat{p}(C)=0.2 and p ^ ​ ( D ) = 0.2 \\hat{p}(D)=0.2 , the expected probability of seeing C substituted for D is 0.02.\n522\tA positive score means the substitution occurs more often than expected by chance; a negative score means less often.\n523\tSince the ordering in pairwise alignments (which sequence is ‘first’) is arbitrary, substitutions are symmetric (C → \\to D is the same as D → \\to C).\n524\tThus there are 78 78 unique scores – 12 diagonal, and 66 off-diagonal.\n525\tSubstitution Distance.\n526\tWe compute substitution rate as a function of the absolute interval size between substituted notes.\n527\tWe use transposed MIDI pitch vectors, 𝐱 τ \\mathbf{x}_{\\tau} , rather than pitch class vectors here, because pitch class differences obscure direction and changes greater than an octave – e.g.\n528\t, a C → D \\textrm{C}\\to\\textrm{D} substitution could represent + 2 +2 , − 10 -10 , or even + 14 +14 semitones.\n529\tFor each aligned pair, we take the absolute difference between pitch vectors elementwise to get a vector of substitution distances, then compute the distribution over distances from 1 - 13 semitones 113\\text{\\,}\\mathrm{s}\\mathrm{e}\\mathrm{m}\\mathrm{i}\\mathrm{t}\\mathrm{o}\\mathrm{n}\\mathrm{e}\\mathrm{s} ; there are larger intervals than this, but they become increasingly scarce with size.\n530\tTo normalize, we compute the expected distribution – the distribution of interval sizes one would obtain by randomly pairing any two notes within the same melody.\n531\tWe use the observed distribution of all pairwise pitch differences within each melody as a proxy for this.\n532\tThis expected distribution is computed only from melodies that appear in matched pairs, with each melody weighted by how many pairs it participates in.\n533\tThe normalized substitution rate at each distance is then the ratio of the observed to the expected probability, reported on a log scale.\n534\tPosition Substitution Rate.\n535\tFor each aligned pair of parts, we compute a binary vector indicating whether a substitution occurs at each grid position.\n536\tFor cases where the grid is finer than an eighth note, we limit our search to grid positions that coincide with multiples of eighth notes.\n537\tWe calculate the number of substitutions that occur at each within-measure position k k , given in integer units of eighth notes, and divide by the number of measures N measure N_{\\textrm{measure}} to get the position substitution rate for a pair of parts.\n538\tThe overall rate is then a weighted average across all pairs of parts.\n539\tCovariance and Repetition.\n540\tFor a set of N p N_{p} aligned pairs of pitch vectors ( 𝐱 τ , 𝐱 τ ′ ) (\\mathbf{x}_{\\tau},\\mathbf{x}_{\\tau}^{\\prime}) of length L L , we convert each pair into a boolean match vector 𝐛 \\mathbf{b} , where b i = 1 b_{i}=1 if the two vectors agree at position i i and b i = 0 b_{i}=0 otherwise.\n541\tWe collect these vectors into an N p × L N_{p}\\times L match matrix 𝐁 \\mathbf{B} , and let μ i \\mu_{i} denote the weighted mean of column i i , i.e.\n542\t, the mean match rate at position i i .\n543\tThroughout this section, angle brackets ⟨ ⋅ ⟩ w \\langle\\cdot\\rangle_{w} denote a weighted average over all N p N_{p} pairs (see Sample Weighting).\n544\tWe then compute the L × L L\\times L sequence covariance matrix Σ i ​ j = Cov ⁡ ( 𝐁 i , 𝐁 j ) = ⟨ ( b i − μ i ) ​ ( b j − μ j ) ⟩ w .\n545\t\\Sigma_{ij}=\\operatorname{Cov}(\\mathbf{B}_{i},\\mathbf{B}_{j})=\\langle(b_{i}-\\mu_{i})(b_{j}-\\mu_{j})\\rangle_{w}.\n546\tEach entry Σ i ​ j \\Sigma_{ij} measures how often positions i i and j j tend to match or mismatch together: a score of 1 1 indicates that they always covary (always matching or always mismatching across pairs), and a score of − 1 -1 indicates the opposite.\n547\tWe deviate from traditional practice in one aspect: we measure covariance using grouped pairwise alignments for tunes (including unrelated tunes) with the same meter; for proteins covariance is computed using multiple-sequence alignments of related sequences.\n548\tThis methodological choice is apt because the dance tunes have such rigid structures which permits alignment of any tunes with the same meter, and is suitable for evaluating repetition within a musical style.\n549\tTo isolate the contribution of repetition to this covariance, we compute a second matrix that provides an exact partition of Σ \\Sigma .\n550\tFor each aligned pair, define the L × L L\\times L boolean linked repetition matrix R R , such that R i ​ j = 1 R_{ij}=1 when positions i i and j j have the same pitch within 𝐱 τ \\mathbf{x}_{\\tau} and within 𝐱 τ ′ \\mathbf{x}_{\\tau}^{\\prime} simultaneously.\n551\tThe repetition covariance matrix, Σ i ​ j rep = ⟨ R i ​ j ​ ( b i − μ i ) ​ ( b j − μ j ) ⟩ w , \\Sigma^{\\mathrm{rep}}_{ij}=\\langle R_{ij}(b_{i}-\\mu_{i})(b_{j}-\\mu_{j})\\rangle_{w}, together with its complement Σ i ​ j − Σ i ​ j rep \\Sigma_{ij}-\\Sigma^{\\mathrm{rep}}_{ij} exactly partitions the sequence covariance into contributions from repetition-linked position pairs and all others.\n552\tProtein Analyses We use two proteins as illustrative examples: cytochrome c (UniProt P00004) and thioredoxin (P0AA25).\n553\tFor cytochrome c we retrieve orthologous sequences by running BLASTP 103 against SwissProt (minimum PID 50 % 50\\text{\\,}\\% , minimum query coverage 80 % 80\\text{\\,}\\% ; top 200 200 hits), fetch hit sequences from NCBI Entrez, 104 and build a multiple sequence alignment with MAFFT.\n554\t105 Structures are downloaded from the AlphaFold Protein Structure Database.\n555\t106 Substitution matrix.\n556\tWe report BLOSUM62, 18 the standard log-odds amino acid substitution matrix computed using blocks of conserved protein regions with PID ≥ 62 \\textrm{PID}\\geq 62 .\n557\tPositional conservation.\n558\tFor each alignment column at which the query has no gap, we compute sequence identity as the frequency of the consensus (most common) amino acid among the non-gap entries (Fig.\n559\t2 E, top).\n560\tRelative solvent accessibility.\n561\tSolvent accessibility is a common metric used to describe how much an amino acid is exposed to solvent, as opposed to buried inside the folded structure.\n562\tPer-position solvent-accessible surface area is computed from each AlphaFold structure using the Shrake-Rupley algorithm 107 and normalised by the empirical Gly-X-Gly maxima for each amino acid type to give relative solvent accessibility (RSA).\n563\tResidue-level RSA values are mapped onto alignment columns, and for each reference position we take the mean RSA across all aligned orthologues with an available AlphaFold structure (Fig.\n564\t2 E, bottom).\n565\tContact map.\n566\tA contact map is a 2D representation of protein structure, indicating which sequence positions are close together.\n567\tWe compute the contact map from the AlphaFold structure of thioredoxin by taking all pairwise C α -C α distances and thresholding at 0.8 nm 0.8\\text{\\,}\\mathrm{n}\\mathrm{m} .\n568\tMusicological Analyses Mode Estimation.\n569\tThere are four 7-note modes associated with Irish dance tunes, which can be represented as sets of scale degrees – pitch class measured in semitones from the tonic – that correspond to the number of semitones from the tonic: • Major: [0, 2, 4 , 5, 7, 9 , 11 ] • Mixolydian: [0, 2, 4 , 5, 7, 9 , 10 ] • Minor: [0, 2, 3 , 5, 7, 8 , 10 ] • Dorian: [0, 2, 3 , 5, 7, 9 , 10 ] The highlighted scale degrees are those that distinguish the four modes.\n570\tSince the mode annotations given by users are not always correct, we use a simple decision tree to automatically annotate modes based on pitch class histograms (see Supplementary Section 2).\n571\tSome tunes do not have all seven pitch classes, and are labelled ‘Major pentatonic’, ‘Minor pentatonic’, ‘Minor/Dorian’, ‘Mixolydian/Dorian’, or ‘indeterminate’.\n572\tWhen analysing pairs of parts separated into the four main modes, we group pairs based on whether the modes of both parts are compatible with the target mode.\n573\tThe most conservative compatibility criterion is that the part mode must equal the target mode.\n574\tThe least conservative criterion is that the part mode must be a subset of the target mode – e.g.\n575\t, if ‘Minor’ is the target, then ‘Minor pentatonic’ and ‘Minor/Dorian’ are compatible.\n576\tWe use the least conservative criterion for our main analyses, and confirm that we get similar results using the most conservative criterion.\n577\tKey Estimation.\n578\tThere are many algorithms for estimating the key signature of a piece of music.\n579\tGiven that they are trained on popular and classical music, they are poorly suited to the modal character of Irish folk music.\n580\tThus we adapt the well-known Krumhansl-Schmuckler algorithm for estimating key, 108 using the statistics of TheSession tunes.\n581\tThe Krumhansl-Schmuckler algorithm uses two modal profiles (Major and Minor), pitch-class histograms averaged over tunes with the same mode.\n582\tWe create four modal profiles by separating tunes into the four main modes, transposing them to the key of ‘C’, and computing the pitch class histogram.\n583\tFor each mode, we get the average pitch class histogram over all tunes that are assigned the exact mode (see Mode Estimation).\n584\tWe obtain an overall key-finding accuracy of 76 % 76\\text{\\,}\\% ; we could use a more sophisticed approach to achieve higher accuracy 109 , however this is sufficient for our purpose of demonstrating differences between conserved and non-conserved notes.\n585\tMelodic Interval Distribution.\n586\tFor each tune, we compute the melodic interval sequence by taking the absolute difference between consecutive pitches in the MIDI pitch sequence 𝐱 \\mathbf{x} .\n587\tWe count the occurrences of each interval value within each tune and normalise by the total count to get a per-tune distribution.\n588\tThe overall distribution is then a weighted average across all tunes.\n589\tOnset Probability (Rhythmic Strength).\n590\tFor each tune, we compute a histogram of note onset positions within a measure, where position is measured in units of eighth notes from the start of the measure.\n591\tWe only consider integer values.\n592\tThe onset probability is the weighted mean of this histogram across all tunes, giving the empirical probability that a note onset occurs at within-measure position k k .\n593\tData and Code Availability Code is available at github.com/jomimc/TheSessionEvo and data is available at zenodo.org/records/21356647 .\n594\tAI Usage Declaration Claude was used for analysis code and for copyediting the manuscript.\n595\tThe authors assume full responsibility for both.\n596\tAuthor Contributions Conceptualization: JMM, WTF.\n597\tMethodology: JMM.\n598\tSoftware: JMM.\n599\tFormal Analysis: JMM.\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you