e absolute interval size between substituted notes.\nWe use transposed MIDI pitch vectors, 𝐱 τ \\mathbf{x}_{\\tau} , rather than pitch class vectors here, because pitch class differences obscure direction and changes greater than an octave – e.g.\n, a C → D \\textrm{C}\\to\\textrm{D} substitution could represent + 2 +2 , − 10 -10 , or even + 14 +14 semitones.\nFor each aligned pair, we take the absolute difference between pitch vectors elementwise to get a vector of substitution distances, then compute the distribution over distances from 1 - 13 semitones 113\\text{\\,}\\mathrm{s}\\mathrm{e}\\mathrm{m}\\mathrm{i}\\mathrm{t}\\mathrm{o}\\mathrm{n}\\mathrm{e}\\mathrm{s} ; there are larger intervals than this, but they become increasingly scarce with size.\nTo normalize, we compute the expected distribution – the distribution of interval sizes one would obtain by randomly pairing any two notes within the same melody.\nWe use the observed distribution of all pairwise pitch differences within each melody as a proxy for this.\nThis expected distribution is computed only from melodies that appear in matched pairs, with each melody weighted by how many pairs it participates in.\nThe normalized substitution rate at each distance is then the ratio of the observed to the expected probability, reported on a log scale.\nPosition Substitution Rate.\nFor each aligned pair of parts, we compute a binary vector indicating whether a substitution occurs at each grid position.\nFor cases where the grid is finer than an eighth note, we limit our search to grid positions that coincide with multiples of eighth notes.\nWe calculate the number of substitutions that occur at each within-measure position k k , given in integer units of eighth notes, and divide by the number of measures N measure N_{\\textrm{measure}} to get the position substitution rate for a pair of parts.\nThe overall rate is then a weighted average across all pairs of parts.\nCovariance and Repetition.\nFor a set of N p N_{p} aligned pairs of pitch vectors ( 𝐱 τ , 𝐱 τ ′ ) (\\mathbf{x}_{\\tau},\\mathbf{x}_{\\tau}^{\\prime}) of length L L , we convert each pair into a boolean match vector 𝐛 \\mathbf{b} , where b i = 1 b_{i}=1 if the two vectors agree at position i i and b i = 0 b_{i}=0 otherwise.\nWe collect these vectors into an N p × L N_{p}\\times L match matrix 𝐁 \\mathbf{B} , and let μ i \\mu_{i} denote the weighted mean of column i i , i.e.\n, the mean match rate at position i i .\nThroughout this section, angle brackets ⟨ ⋅ ⟩ w \\langle\\cdot\\rangle_{w} denote a weighted average over all N p N_{p} pairs (see Sample Weighting).\nWe then compute the L × L L\\times L sequence covariance matrix Σ i ​ j = Cov ⁡ ( 𝐁 i , 𝐁 j ) = ⟨ ( b i − μ i ) ​ ( b j − μ j ) ⟩ w .\n\\Sigma_{ij}=\\operatorname{Cov}(\\mathbf{B}_{i},\\mathbf{B}_{j})=\\langle(b_{i}-\\mu_{i})(b_{j}-\\mu_{j})\\rangle_{w}.\nEach entry Σ i ​ j \\Sigma_{ij} measures how often positions i i and j j tend to match or mismatch together: a score of 1 1 indicates that they always covary (always matching or always mismatching across pairs), and a score of − 1 -1 indicates the opposite.\nWe deviate from traditional practice in one aspect: we measure covariance using grouped pairwise alignments for tunes (including unrelated tunes) with the same meter; for proteins covariance is computed using multiple-sequence alignments of related sequences.\nThis methodological choice is apt because the dance tunes have such rigid structures which permits alignment of any tunes with the same meter, and is suitable for evaluating repetition within a musical style.\nTo isolate the contribution of repetition to this covariance, we compute a second matrix that provides an exact partition of Σ \\Sigma .\nFor each aligned pair, define the L × L L\\times L boolean linked repetition matrix R R , such that R i ​ j = 1 R_{ij}=1 when positions i i and j j have the same pitch within 𝐱 τ \\mathbf{x}_{\\tau} and within 𝐱 τ ′ \\mathbf{x}_{\\tau}^{\\prime} simultaneously.\nThe repetition covariance matrix, Σ i ​ j rep = ⟨ R i ​ j ​ ( b i − μ i ) ​ ( b j − μ j ) ⟩ w , \\Sigma^{\\mathrm{rep}}_{ij}=\\langle R_{ij}(b_{i}-\\mu_{i})(b_{j}-\\mu_{j})\\rangle_{w}, together with its complement Σ i ​ j − Σ i ​ j rep \\Sigma_{ij}-\\Sigma^{\\mathrm{rep}}_{ij} exactly partitions the sequence covariance into contributions from repetition-linked position pairs and all others.\nProtein Analyses We use two proteins as illustrative examples: cytochrome c (UniProt P00004) and thioredoxin (P0AA25).\nFor cytochrome c we retrieve orthologous sequences by running BLASTP 103 against SwissProt (minimum PID 50 % 50\\text{\\,}\\% , minimum query coverage 80 % 80\\text{\\,}\\% ; top 200 200 hits), fetch hit sequences from NCBI Entrez, 104 and build a multiple sequence alignment with MAFFT.\n105 Structures are downloaded from the AlphaFold Protein Structure Database.\n106 Substitution matrix.\nWe report BLOSUM62, 18 the standard log-odds amino acid substitution matrix computed using blocks of conserved protein regions with PID ≥ 62 \\textrm{PID}\\geq 62 .\nPositional conservation.\nFor each alignment column at which the query has no gap, we compute sequence identity as the frequency of the consensus (most common) amino acid among the non-gap entries (Fig.\n2 E, top).\nRelative solvent accessibility.\nSolvent accessibility is a common metric used to describe how much an amino acid is exposed to solvent, as opposed to buried inside the folded structure.\nPer-position solvent-accessible surface area is computed from each AlphaFold structure using the Shrake-Rupley algorithm 107 and normalised by the empirical Gly-X-Gly maxima for each amino acid type to give relative solvent accessibility (RSA).\nResidue-level RSA values are mapped onto alignment columns, and for each reference position we take the mean RSA across all aligned orthologues with an available AlphaFold structure (Fig.\n2 E, bottom).\nContact map.\nA contact map is a 2D representation of protein structure, indicating which sequence positions are close together.\nWe compute the contact map from the AlphaFold structure of thioredoxin by taking all pairwise C α -C α distances and thresholding at 0.8 nm 0.8\\text{\\,}\\mathrm{n}\\mathrm{m} .\nMusicological Analyses Mode Estimation.\nThere are four 7-note modes associated with Irish dance tunes, which can be represented as sets of scale degrees – pitch class measured in semitones from the tonic – that correspond to the number of semitones from the tonic: • Major: [0, 2, 4 , 5, 7, 9 , 11 ] • Mixolydian: [0, 2, 4 , 5, 7, 9 , 10 ] • Minor: [0, 2, 3 , 5, 7, 8 , 10 ] • Dorian: [0, 2, 3 , 5, 7, 9 , 10 ] The highlighted scale degrees are those that distinguish the four modes.\nSince the mode annotations given by users are not always correct, we use a simple decision tree to automatically annotate modes based on pitch class histograms (see Supplementary Section 2).\nSome tunes do not have all seven pitch classes, and are labelled ‘Major pentatonic’, ‘Minor pentatonic’, ‘Minor/Dorian’, ‘Mixolydian/Dorian’, or ‘indeterminate’.\nWhen analysing pairs of parts separated into the four main modes, we group pairs based on whether the modes of both parts are compatible with the target mode.\nThe most conservative compatibility criterion is that the part mode must equal the target mode.\nThe least conservative criterion is that the part mode must be a subset of the target mode – e.g.\n, if ‘Minor’ is the target, then ‘Minor pentatonic’ and ‘Minor/Dorian’ are compatible.\nWe use the least conservative criterion for our main analyses, and confirm that we get similar results using the most conservative criterion.\nKey Estimation.\nThere are many algorithms for estimating the key signature of a piece of music.\nGiven that they are trained on popular and classical music, they are poorly suited to the modal character of Irish folk music.\nThus we adapt the well-known Krumhansl-Schmuckler algorithm for estimating key, 108 using the statistics of TheSession tunes.\nThe Krumhansl-Schmuckler algorithm uses two modal profiles (Major and Minor), pitch-class histograms averaged over tunes with the same mode.\nWe create four modal profiles by separating tunes into the four main modes, transposing them to the key of ‘C’, and computing the pitch class histogram.\nFor each mode, we get the average pitch class histogram over all tunes that are assigned the exact mode (see Mode Estimation).\nWe obtain an overall key-finding accuracy of 76 % 76\\text{\\,}\\% ; we could use a more sophisticed approach to achieve higher accuracy 109 , however this is sufficient for our purpose of demonstrating differences between conserved and non-conserved notes.\nMelodic Interval Distribution.\nFor each tune, we compute the melodic interval sequence by taking the absolute difference between consecutive pitches in the MIDI pitch sequence 𝐱 \\mathbf{x} .\nWe count the occurrences of each interval value within each tune and normalise by the total count to get a per-tune distribution.\nThe overall distribution is then a weighted average across all tunes.\nOnset Probability (Rhythmic Strength).\nFor each tune, we compute a histogram of note onset positions within a measure, where position is measured in units of eighth notes from the start of the measure.\nWe only consider integer values.\nThe onset probability is the weighted mean of this histogram across all tunes, giving the empirical probability that a note onset occurs at within-measure position k k .\nData and Code Availability Code is available at github.com/jomimc/TheSessionEvo and data is available at zenodo.org/records/21356647 .\nAI Usage Declaration Claude was used for analysis code and for copyediting the manuscript.\nThe authors assume full responsibility for both.\nAuthor Contributions Conceptualization: JMM, WTF.\nMethodology: JMM.\nSoftware: JMM.\nFormal Analysis: JMM.", "numLines": 100, "startLine": 500, "totalLines": 1272}}}
